1
00:03:20,367 --> 00:03:24,204
Daddy, you're sure I've
never been to Africa before?

2
00:03:24,287 --> 00:03:26,039
It looks familiar.

3
00:03:26,873 --> 00:03:30,627
You saw the same scenery
last summer driving to Las Vegas.

4
00:03:30,711 --> 00:03:33,797
Sure. Where Daddy lost
all that money at the crap...

5
00:03:33,880 --> 00:03:34,965
Hey!

6
00:03:35,048 --> 00:03:36,800
...table.

7
00:03:38,301 --> 00:03:40,137
Hey, look! A camel.

8
00:03:44,808 --> 00:03:47,310
Of course this isn't really Africa,
honey. It's the French Morocco.

9
00:03:47,394 --> 00:03:48,854
Well, it's northern
Africa.

10
00:03:48,937 --> 00:03:50,564
Still seems
like Las Vegas.

11
00:03:50,647 --> 00:03:52,607
We're just 100 miles
north of the Sahara desert.

12
00:03:52,691 --> 00:03:54,526
Do you realize
that, son?

13
00:03:54,609 --> 00:03:58,238
I don't know. In school, they
call this the dark continent.

14
00:03:58,321 --> 00:04:00,741
This is twice as
bright as Indianapolis.

15
00:04:00,824 --> 00:04:03,034
You just wait till
we get to Marrakech.

16
00:04:03,118 --> 00:04:05,579
Marrakesh?
Sounds like a drink.

17
00:04:06,830 --> 00:04:08,373
It sure does.

18
00:04:40,447 --> 00:04:41,865
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

19
00:04:41,948 --> 00:04:43,283
Hold on here.
What's the matter?

20
00:05:04,679 --> 00:05:07,307
Well, I sure want
to thank you.

21
00:05:07,390 --> 00:05:09,643
Without your help, anything
might have happened here.

22
00:05:09,726 --> 00:05:11,436
<i>My Measure,
monsieur.</i>

23
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:14,523
There are moments in life
when we all need a little help.

24
00:05:14,606 --> 00:05:17,651
Yeah. Just what
was the trouble?

25
00:05:17,734 --> 00:05:20,821
Your little boy accidentally
pulled off his wife's veil.

26
00:05:20,904 --> 00:05:21,947
You know?
Yeah.

27
00:05:22,906 --> 00:05:23,990
Hank!

28
00:05:24,074 --> 00:05:25,325
I want to introduce
my wife, Mrs. McKenna.

29
00:05:25,408 --> 00:05:27,035
How do you do?
How do you do, madame?

30
00:05:27,118 --> 00:05:28,453
My name is
Louis Bernard.

31
00:05:29,079 --> 00:05:31,039
Well, we thank you
very much, Mr. Bernard.

32
00:05:31,122 --> 00:05:32,290
That's our son, Hank.

33
00:05:32,374 --> 00:05:33,458
Hello, Hank.

34
00:05:33,542 --> 00:05:35,502
Hello.
You talk Arab talk.

35
00:05:36,461 --> 00:05:37,587
A few words.

36
00:05:37,671 --> 00:05:39,923
Why was he so angry?
It was just an accident.

37
00:05:40,006 --> 00:05:44,219
But the Muslim religion
allows for few accidents.

38
00:05:44,469 --> 00:05:46,179
Yeah, I suppose so.

39
00:05:46,263 --> 00:05:47,264
May I...

40
00:05:47,347 --> 00:05:49,266
Yeah, sit down right
in front of Jo there.

41
00:05:50,016 --> 00:05:52,894
I thought
his name was Hank.

42
00:05:52,978 --> 00:05:56,481
No, it's my wife's name.
You see, Jâ€”O. No "."E

43
00:05:56,565 --> 00:05:57,691
How different.

44
00:05:57,774 --> 00:05:58,900
It's short
for Josephine.

45
00:05:58,984 --> 00:06:01,528
I've called her that so long nobody
knows her by any other name.

46
00:06:01,611 --> 00:06:02,612
No. Do they?

47
00:06:02,696 --> 00:06:03,738
I do. Mommy.

48
00:06:03,822 --> 00:06:05,031
Yeah.
Forgot about that.

49
00:06:05,115 --> 00:06:06,825
Now, about
the accident.

50
00:06:06,908 --> 00:06:09,953
You see, a Muslim woman
never takes off her veil in public

51
00:06:10,078 --> 00:06:11,663
under any circumstances. I see.

52
00:06:11,746 --> 00:06:13,206
You mean they feed
intravenously?

53
00:06:13,290 --> 00:06:14,374
No, Hank.

54
00:06:14,457 --> 00:06:17,252
What a big word
for such a small boy.

55
00:06:17,419 --> 00:06:19,296
You see,
I'm a doctor.

56
00:06:19,379 --> 00:06:20,839
Well,
he sounds like one.

57
00:06:22,007 --> 00:06:24,050
Yeah.
He can spell hemoglobin.

58
00:06:24,134 --> 00:06:27,262
Of course, he has a little trouble
with words like dog and cat.

59
00:06:29,347 --> 00:06:31,141
Where do you
practice, Doctor?

60
00:06:31,224 --> 00:06:34,519
Indianapolis, Indiana. Good
Samaritan Hospital out there.

61
00:06:34,603 --> 00:06:36,521
What brings you
to Marrakech?

62
00:06:36,605 --> 00:06:39,274
You see, we were attending
a medical convention in Paris.

63
00:06:39,357 --> 00:06:40,817
And I thought as much as
as we were in Europe,

64
00:06:40,901 --> 00:06:43,320
I'd come down and
see Morocco again.

65
00:06:43,778 --> 00:06:46,031
Daddy liberated
Africa.

66
00:06:46,114 --> 00:06:48,742
Well, I was stationed
up in Casablanca

67
00:06:48,825 --> 00:06:51,536
at an army field hospital
during the war.

68
00:06:51,995 --> 00:06:53,872
Do you live in Morocco,
Mr. Bernard?

69
00:06:53,955 --> 00:06:54,956
No.

70
00:06:55,665 --> 00:06:57,834
I suppose you came
directly from Paris.

71
00:06:57,918 --> 00:07:00,295
We looked in on
Lisbon and Rome.

72
00:07:00,378 --> 00:07:01,630
And Casablanca.

73
00:07:01,713 --> 00:07:02,923
And Casablanca.

74
00:07:04,257 --> 00:07:06,885
I hope you will have time
to truly enjoy Marrakech.

75
00:07:07,177 --> 00:07:10,555
Well, let's see. We'll have
at the most about three days.

76
00:07:10,639 --> 00:07:15,685
You will naturally be stopping at
the hotels La Mamounia or La Menara.

77
00:07:15,769 --> 00:07:17,479
Why do you ask?

78
00:07:17,562 --> 00:07:20,649
Because they are hotels
for tourists of good taste.

79
00:07:22,192 --> 00:07:23,777
Do you live in
France, Mr. Bernard?

80
00:07:23,860 --> 00:07:24,861
Sometimes.

81
00:07:24,945 --> 00:07:26,112
Do you eat snails?

82
00:07:26,196 --> 00:07:28,573
When I'm lucky
enough to get them.

83
00:07:28,657 --> 00:07:31,451
Well, if you ever get hungry, our
garden back home is full of snails.

84
00:07:31,534 --> 00:07:32,786
Thank you for
the invitation.

85
00:07:33,954 --> 00:07:36,623
That's all right. We tried
everything to get rid of them.

86
00:07:36,706 --> 00:07:38,416
We never thought
of a Frenchman.

87
00:08:36,891 --> 00:08:38,518
Here we go.

88
00:08:39,519 --> 00:08:41,980
Say, do you want to share a
taxi with us down to the hotel?

89
00:08:42,063 --> 00:08:43,732
That's kind of you,
Doctor,

90
00:08:43,815 --> 00:08:45,775
but unfortunately, I
have some business first.

91
00:08:45,859 --> 00:08:46,860
I see.

92
00:08:46,943 --> 00:08:48,570
What business are
you in, Mr. Bernard?

93
00:08:48,653 --> 00:08:51,656
However, I'll be there later. Perhaps
we might have a drink together.

94
00:08:51,740 --> 00:08:53,867
Well, no, come up to our
suite. We'll have a drink up there.

95
00:08:53,950 --> 00:08:55,702
In that case, I will
take you to dinner.

96
00:08:55,785 --> 00:08:57,454
No, that's not fair.

97
00:08:57,537 --> 00:08:58,663
But I know Marrakesh.

98
00:08:58,747 --> 00:09:00,498
I can show you an
intriguing Arab restaurant

99
00:09:00,582 --> 00:09:03,126
where the food is different
and the manner of eating exotic.

100
00:09:03,209 --> 00:09:05,879
Well, that's what we came
here for. How about it, Jo?

101
00:09:05,962 --> 00:09:07,630
How about one of
those Arabian nights?

102
00:09:07,714 --> 00:09:09,132
I'd love it.

103
00:09:09,215 --> 00:09:12,677
How would you prefer to travel
to the hotel? By taxi, fiacre?

104
00:09:12,761 --> 00:09:13,720
Gee, I don't know.

105
00:09:13,803 --> 00:09:15,930
A wagon! I wanna
ride in a wagon!

106
00:09:16,931 --> 00:09:18,058
Well, I guess
it's a wagon.

107
00:09:18,141 --> 00:09:19,684
See you later.

108
00:09:19,768 --> 00:09:22,020
Au revoir. I look
forward to the cocktails.

109
00:09:22,103 --> 00:09:23,146
Good-bye. Come on.

110
00:09:23,229 --> 00:09:24,522
Bye.

111
00:09:25,940 --> 00:09:28,985
Hank, you sit up
with the driver.

112
00:09:29,069 --> 00:09:32,113
How do you like this?
A horse-drawn convertible.

113
00:09:46,086 --> 00:09:48,421
Well, I just saw Louis
Bernard talking to that Arab.

114
00:09:48,505 --> 00:09:49,547
What Arab?

115
00:09:49,631 --> 00:09:51,591
The one that was shouting
at Hank for pulling the veil off.

116
00:09:51,674 --> 00:09:53,468
They were talking like
they were very dear friends.

117
00:09:53,551 --> 00:09:56,846
Well, he probably knew him
before. What does that mean?

118
00:09:56,930 --> 00:10:00,433
It means that Mr. Bernard
is a very mysterious man.

119
00:10:00,517 --> 00:10:03,353
What? He seemed
perfectly normal to me.

120
00:10:04,479 --> 00:10:06,314
Now, what do you
really know about him?

121
00:10:06,397 --> 00:10:08,024
What do I know about
him? I know his name.

122
00:10:08,108 --> 00:10:09,692
We were sitting there.
We were talking.

123
00:10:09,776 --> 00:10:11,736
You don't know anything
about this man,

124
00:10:11,820 --> 00:10:14,447
and he knows everything
there is to know about you.

125
00:10:14,531 --> 00:10:15,824
Wait.

126
00:10:15,907 --> 00:10:18,284
He knows that you live
in Indianapolis, Indiana.

127
00:10:18,368 --> 00:10:21,371
He knows that you're a doctor
at the Good Samaritan Hospital.

128
00:10:21,454 --> 00:10:24,624
And he knows that you attended
a medical convention in Paris,

129
00:10:24,707 --> 00:10:27,168
and that you stopped off in
Rome, and Lisbon and Casablanca

130
00:10:27,252 --> 00:10:28,461
for just a few days.

131
00:10:28,545 --> 00:10:29,629
All right.

132
00:10:29,712 --> 00:10:34,217
And he knows that you served in
north Africa in an army field hospital.

133
00:10:34,300 --> 00:10:37,679
Honey, it was just a casual
conversation. That's all.

134
00:10:37,762 --> 00:10:39,806
Darling, you weren't
just talking casually.

135
00:10:39,889 --> 00:10:43,184
He was asking all kinds of questions,
and you were answering them.

136
00:10:43,268 --> 00:10:45,019
You might as well have
handed him your passport.

137
00:10:45,103 --> 00:10:46,271
Well, what's
the difference?

138
00:10:46,354 --> 00:10:49,649
We just have a conversation.
I've got nothing to hide.

139
00:10:49,732 --> 00:10:52,193
I have a feeling
that Mr. Bernard has.

140
00:10:52,277 --> 00:10:53,528
Honey.

141
00:10:53,611 --> 00:10:55,822
I know this is
mysterious Morocco,

142
00:10:55,905 --> 00:10:58,616
but we're not going to
lose our head, are we?

143
00:10:58,700 --> 00:11:00,535
I know.
I know what it is.

144
00:11:00,618 --> 00:11:01,619
What?

145
00:11:01,703 --> 00:11:05,415
Why, you're sore because this
fella didn't ask you any questions.

146
00:11:05,498 --> 00:11:06,833
Hardy-har-har.

147
00:11:06,916 --> 00:11:08,585
<i>Hardy-hat.</i>

148
00:11:50,251 --> 00:11:51,961
Well, this eases
the pain.

149
00:11:52,045 --> 00:11:53,713
What pain, Mommy?

150
00:11:53,796 --> 00:11:54,797
It's just an expression, honey.

151
00:11:54,839 --> 00:11:56,299
Hey, can you take care
of the driver? Yes, sir.

152
00:11:56,382 --> 00:11:58,051
My name is McKenna,
Dr. McKenna.

153
00:11:58,134 --> 00:11:59,302
I'll take care of
everything, sir.

154
00:12:05,266 --> 00:12:06,351
Come on.

155
00:12:06,434 --> 00:12:07,435
We're being watched.

156
00:12:07,518 --> 00:12:09,479
What? Come on!

157
00:12:24,494 --> 00:12:28,414
Que <i>sera, sera</i>

158
00:12:28,498 --> 00:12:31,584
<i>What will be, will be</i>

159
00:12:31,668 --> 00:12:36,297
<i>When I was just a little boy</i>

160
00:12:36,381 --> 00:12:41,052
<i>I asked my mother
what will I be</i>

161
00:12:41,135 --> 00:12:42,470
He'll make
a fine doctor.

162
00:12:42,553 --> 00:12:47,475
<i>Will I be handsome?
Will I be rich?</i>

163
00:12:47,558 --> 00:12:49,269
<i>Here's what she said to me</i>

164
00:12:49,352 --> 00:12:51,646
Come on, darling.

165
00:12:51,729 --> 00:12:55,775
<i>Que sera, sera</i>

166
00:12:55,858 --> 00:13:00,196
<i>Whatever will be,
will be</i>

167
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:04,284
<i>The future's
not ours to see</i>

168
00:13:04,367 --> 00:13:07,453
<i>Que sera, sera</i>

169
00:13:08,705 --> 00:13:12,208
<i>What will be, will be</i>

170
00:13:12,292 --> 00:13:13,960
Second verse.

171
00:13:14,043 --> 00:13:18,381
<i>When I was
just a child in school</i>

172
00:13:18,464 --> 00:13:23,052
<i>I asked my teacher
what should I try</i>

173
00:13:23,136 --> 00:13:24,387
Catch.

174
00:13:24,470 --> 00:13:29,183
<i>Should I paint pictures?
Should I sing songs?</i>

175
00:13:29,267 --> 00:13:32,812
<i>This was her wise reply</i>

176
00:13:32,895 --> 00:13:36,941
<i>Que sera, sera</i>

177
00:13:37,066 --> 00:13:41,321
<i>Whatever will be, will
be</i>

178
00:13:41,404 --> 00:13:45,491
<i>The future's not
ours to see</i>

179
00:13:45,575 --> 00:13:48,202
<i>Que sera, sera</i>

180
00:13:48,286 --> 00:13:49,871
Oops!

181
00:13:49,954 --> 00:13:53,333
<i>What will be, will be</i>

182
00:13:53,416 --> 00:13:55,209
May I have this next dance? Yes.

183
00:13:55,293 --> 00:13:56,294
All right.

184
00:14:02,842 --> 00:14:04,927
You're divine.

185
00:14:10,767 --> 00:14:11,893
Dinner for the boy.

186
00:14:11,976 --> 00:14:14,729
Yeah, come in. Right
around the corner.

187
00:14:17,857 --> 00:14:20,735
I can't tell you how
beautifully your wife sings.

188
00:14:20,818 --> 00:14:21,819
Pretty good,
isn't she?

189
00:14:21,903 --> 00:14:24,030
She's marvelous.

190
00:14:24,113 --> 00:14:25,990
Too bad it was
interrupted.

191
00:14:26,074 --> 00:14:28,284
I had that same feeling
myself many times.

192
00:14:28,868 --> 00:14:29,869
Well, everything's fine.

193
00:14:29,952 --> 00:14:31,079
The manager has
a babysitter for us.

194
00:14:31,162 --> 00:14:32,205
Good.

195
00:14:32,288 --> 00:14:34,791
Mrs. McKenna, permit me the
pleasure of serving you a drink.

196
00:14:34,874 --> 00:14:36,793
I would love it.
Thank you.

197
00:14:36,876 --> 00:14:39,962
Were you on the American
stage, Mrs. McKenna?

198
00:14:43,549 --> 00:14:46,135
Yes, Mr. Bernard, I was
on the American stage,

199
00:14:46,219 --> 00:14:47,804
and the London stage,
and the Paris stage.

200
00:14:49,389 --> 00:14:51,891
I thought perhaps you had
seen me in Paris, being French.

201
00:14:51,974 --> 00:14:54,811
You know, the
theater requires time,

202
00:14:54,894 --> 00:14:57,522
and for me, time
is often a luxury.

203
00:14:59,315 --> 00:15:02,652
Have you ever been
to Paris, Mr. Bernard?

204
00:15:02,735 --> 00:15:04,153
I was born there.

205
00:15:12,120 --> 00:15:14,205
What business are you in?

206
00:15:14,288 --> 00:15:17,041
I buy and sell.

207
00:15:17,458 --> 00:15:18,501
What?

208
00:15:19,335 --> 00:15:20,878
Whatever gives
the best profit.

209
00:15:24,882 --> 00:15:26,259
Well, now that
you're in Marrakech,

210
00:15:26,342 --> 00:15:28,261
what are you
buying and selling?

211
00:15:28,344 --> 00:15:32,640
You know, I would much
rather talk about the stage.

212
00:15:32,723 --> 00:15:34,434
If you tell me what
shows you are in...

213
00:15:36,352 --> 00:15:38,855
Would you excuse me?
I'll get it.

214
00:15:38,938 --> 00:15:39,939
No, I got it.

215
00:15:40,022 --> 00:15:41,190
No, IWill.

216
00:15:58,875 --> 00:16:01,586
I'm inquiring for the room
of Monsieur Montgomery.

217
00:16:01,669 --> 00:16:03,880
He asked me for
a drink, and I...

218
00:16:03,963 --> 00:16:05,882
I'm sorry. There's
no Montgomery here.

219
00:16:05,965 --> 00:16:08,301
Pardon me, monsieur.
I regret disturbing you.

220
00:16:08,384 --> 00:16:09,510
Okay.

221
00:16:20,563 --> 00:16:21,606
May I use your
telephone, please?

222
00:16:21,689 --> 00:16:22,690
Yeah, sure.
It's right there.

223
00:16:22,773 --> 00:16:23,983
Mommy!
Yes?

224
00:16:24,066 --> 00:16:25,526
I can't
cut this meat.

225
00:16:25,610 --> 00:16:27,612
IWIdoitforyou,
dean

226
00:16:36,746 --> 00:16:38,122
Hello?

227
00:16:52,512 --> 00:16:55,515
I'm terribly sorry, but I cannot
go to dinner with you tonight.

228
00:16:56,724 --> 00:16:58,309
I have neglected
an important matter

229
00:16:58,392 --> 00:17:00,102
which now requires
my attention.

230
00:17:00,186 --> 00:17:01,270
I see.

231
00:17:01,354 --> 00:17:03,022
Perhaps
another night?

232
00:17:03,105 --> 00:17:05,691
Sure. Sure. We'll
get together again.

233
00:17:05,775 --> 00:17:07,527
Good-bye.
Good-bye.

234
00:17:09,278 --> 00:17:10,988
Good night.
Bye.

235
00:17:12,573 --> 00:17:14,116
Good night.

236
00:17:31,634 --> 00:17:32,635
My name's McKenna.

237
00:17:32,718 --> 00:17:36,305
Of course. The hotel
phoned. Follow me, please.

238
00:17:38,516 --> 00:17:40,226
I think you will
find this comfortable.

239
00:17:40,309 --> 00:17:42,687
Thank you very much.

240
00:18:14,969 --> 00:18:17,221
Honey, move over here.
Let me sit out there.

241
00:18:26,022 --> 00:18:27,940
You're on my dress.

242
00:18:41,537 --> 00:18:42,747
VVhoop!

243
00:18:57,303 --> 00:18:58,804
Yeah.

244
00:18:58,888 --> 00:19:00,556
We always wash the
hands before eating.

245
00:19:09,231 --> 00:19:10,608
Thank you.

246
00:19:17,490 --> 00:19:18,658
VVhoop!

247
00:19:21,410 --> 00:19:22,495
Those people
are staring at us.

248
00:19:22,578 --> 00:19:23,663
What people?

249
00:19:23,746 --> 00:19:25,331
Right in back of us.
What?

250
00:19:25,414 --> 00:19:26,916
Yes.
Here.

251
00:19:27,667 --> 00:19:29,794
They were staring at us
in front of the hotel too.

252
00:19:29,877 --> 00:19:32,380
Jo, will you please
stop imagining things?

253
00:19:32,463 --> 00:19:34,340
I'm not.

254
00:19:34,423 --> 00:19:37,176
Good evening. You must
think me awfully rude.

255
00:19:37,259 --> 00:19:40,388
I've been staring at you ever
since I saw you at the hotel.

256
00:19:40,471 --> 00:19:43,516
You are Jo Conway,
the Jo Conway?

257
00:19:43,599 --> 00:19:44,684
Yes, I am.

258
00:19:44,767 --> 00:19:46,644
Didn't I tell you?
I knew I was right.

259
00:19:46,727 --> 00:19:48,854
I'm Lucy Drayton,
and this is my husband.

260
00:19:48,938 --> 00:19:50,064
How do you do?
How do you do?

261
00:19:50,147 --> 00:19:51,691
We're Dr. and
Mrs. McKenna.

262
00:19:51,774 --> 00:19:53,901
My wife tells me
Mrs. McKenna appeared

263
00:19:53,984 --> 00:19:55,861
at the London Palladium
a few years ago.

264
00:19:55,945 --> 00:19:57,446
Of course, we hardly
ever see a show now.

265
00:19:57,530 --> 00:19:59,073
Edward is such an
old stick in the mud.

266
00:19:59,156 --> 00:20:01,826
So I have to console
myself with your records.

267
00:20:01,951 --> 00:20:03,244
I must admit I love them.

268
00:20:03,327 --> 00:20:05,579
I'm not one for
this terrible bebop

269
00:20:05,663 --> 00:20:07,123
or whatever you
call it.

270
00:20:07,206 --> 00:20:09,917
Thank you very much. When
are you coming back to London?

271
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:12,211
Possibly never again,
professionally.

272
00:20:12,294 --> 00:20:13,379
Don't say you're
giving up the stage.

273
00:20:13,462 --> 00:20:14,880
Well, temporarily,
I am.

274
00:20:14,964 --> 00:20:16,841
Well, it's just
that I'm a doctor,

275
00:20:16,924 --> 00:20:19,009
and you know, a doctor's
wife never has as much time...

276
00:20:19,093 --> 00:20:20,302
What my husband
is trying to say

277
00:20:20,386 --> 00:20:23,472
is Broadway musical shows are
not produced in Indianapolis, Indiana.

278
00:20:23,597 --> 00:20:25,599
Well, you know... Of course,
we could live in New York.

279
00:20:25,683 --> 00:20:28,060
I hear that doctors aren't
starving there either.

280
00:20:28,144 --> 00:20:31,063
Well, it's not that I have any
objection to working in New York.

281
00:20:31,147 --> 00:20:33,065
It's just that it'd be
hard for my patients

282
00:20:33,149 --> 00:20:35,109
to come from
Indianapolis for treatment.

283
00:20:35,192 --> 00:20:37,820
You know, dear, I'm always
saying the wrong thing. I'm sorry.

284
00:20:37,903 --> 00:20:39,071
Not in the least.

285
00:20:39,155 --> 00:20:40,781
Tell me,
Dr. McKenna, do you also go...

286
00:20:40,865 --> 00:20:45,995
Hey, why don't all of you sort of
turn around here or something.

287
00:20:46,078 --> 00:20:47,955
It's kind of kind
of hard on the neck.

288
00:20:49,623 --> 00:20:51,333
It's in one of
our English counties.

289
00:20:51,417 --> 00:20:52,835
It's not what
you'd call a farm.

290
00:20:52,918 --> 00:20:54,587
It's really more
of a small holding.

291
00:20:54,670 --> 00:20:56,172
Here we are.

292
00:20:57,423 --> 00:20:58,549
Isn't that
fascinating?

293
00:20:58,632 --> 00:20:59,675
Yes.

294
00:21:00,468 --> 00:21:02,052
There we are.

295
00:21:06,015 --> 00:21:07,558
Hey, they look good.
Surprise.

296
00:21:07,641 --> 00:21:09,602
They look wonderful.

297
00:21:10,811 --> 00:21:12,730
Looks like bread.

298
00:21:13,689 --> 00:21:15,399
We're not going to
eat all that, are we?

299
00:21:15,483 --> 00:21:16,484
No.

300
00:21:17,860 --> 00:21:19,403
Is that the way you
do it? Just break it?

301
00:21:19,487 --> 00:21:22,448
Yes, just break it. Just
break it. Just like this.

302
00:21:22,531 --> 00:21:25,117
It won't break.
No.

303
00:21:25,201 --> 00:21:27,953
Well, I'm gonna...
There.

304
00:21:28,037 --> 00:21:29,163
Is that the way
you do it?

305
00:21:29,246 --> 00:21:31,207
That's quite all right.

306
00:21:31,290 --> 00:21:33,250
That was
a tough one.

307
00:21:34,376 --> 00:21:35,961
Does it chew any
better than it tears?

308
00:21:38,672 --> 00:21:40,174
Is it fattening?

309
00:21:40,257 --> 00:21:41,842
I imagine
it might be.

310
00:21:42,802 --> 00:21:44,929
No, it's pretty
good,hon.

311
00:21:45,971 --> 00:21:47,139
Well, I...
No plate.

312
00:21:47,223 --> 00:21:48,224
No?
No.

313
00:21:48,307 --> 00:21:49,350
No knife or forks.

314
00:21:49,433 --> 00:21:51,977
That's right. I understand
you're just supposed to dig in.

315
00:21:52,061 --> 00:21:53,979
Allow me to show you,
will you?

316
00:21:54,063 --> 00:21:56,982
You use only the first two
fingers and thumb of the right hand.

317
00:21:57,066 --> 00:21:58,567
You don't use the
other two fingers,

318
00:21:58,651 --> 00:22:00,361
and always the left
hand in the lap.

319
00:22:00,444 --> 00:22:01,570
I see.

320
00:22:01,654 --> 00:22:02,988
May I show you?

321
00:22:03,072 --> 00:22:04,490
Just these two
fingers?

322
00:22:04,573 --> 00:22:07,243
Can I help you?
I'll hold it for you.

323
00:22:15,251 --> 00:22:16,544
That's it.
There we are.

324
00:22:18,963 --> 00:22:20,256
Well...

325
00:22:21,799 --> 00:22:25,010
Boy, could I use this
hand now. I can't...

326
00:22:26,470 --> 00:22:28,264
It's all right. Nobody
minds. No one minds.

327
00:22:28,347 --> 00:22:29,390
That's good style.

328
00:22:29,473 --> 00:22:30,474
No one minds.

329
00:22:30,558 --> 00:22:31,559
It's messy,
but worth it.

330
00:22:31,642 --> 00:22:32,852
I think I'll practice
on an olive.

331
00:22:34,019 --> 00:22:36,856
Honey, it's wonderful.
Here. Take a bite.

332
00:22:36,981 --> 00:22:39,024
Good?
Yeah.

333
00:22:39,108 --> 00:22:40,693
Tell me, does this
way of eating

334
00:22:40,776 --> 00:22:42,278
have to do with
religion or something?

335
00:22:42,361 --> 00:22:44,280
I think it's more
social than religious.

336
00:22:44,363 --> 00:22:45,447
I don't know.

337
00:22:45,531 --> 00:22:48,450
It seems like to me if you have
four good fingers and a thumb,

338
00:22:48,534 --> 00:22:51,370
you ought to be able
to use all of them.

339
00:22:51,453 --> 00:22:52,705
It's very good,
isn't it?

340
00:22:52,788 --> 00:22:53,956
Very good.

341
00:22:54,039 --> 00:22:56,125
Well, as I was saying,

342
00:22:56,208 --> 00:22:59,753
I was quite happy farming my bit
of land down in Buckinghamshire

343
00:22:59,837 --> 00:23:02,464
when these United Nations
fellows started worrying me.

344
00:23:02,548 --> 00:23:04,341
Edward was a big noise
in the Ministry of Food

345
00:23:04,425 --> 00:23:05,718
during the war,
you know.

346
00:23:05,801 --> 00:23:07,344
So we pulled ourselves
up by the roots,

347
00:23:07,428 --> 00:23:10,222
and here we are,
United Nations Relief.

348
00:23:10,306 --> 00:23:11,640
Sounds like
interesting work.

349
00:23:11,724 --> 00:23:15,060
I'm preparing a report on
soil erosion at the moment.

350
00:23:15,144 --> 00:23:16,729
You know,
parts of this country

351
00:23:16,812 --> 00:23:19,064
are not unlike your
Dust Bowl formation.

352
00:23:19,148 --> 00:23:22,568
A thin layer of topsoil
and underneath...

353
00:23:30,701 --> 00:23:33,787
How do you like that? First he
promises to take us to dinner...

354
00:23:33,871 --> 00:23:37,458
Yeah. Well, we just
met him today, honey.

355
00:23:37,541 --> 00:23:39,919
You can't expect him
to change his whole life.

356
00:23:40,002 --> 00:23:41,253
Ben, what's the
matter with you?

357
00:23:41,337 --> 00:23:42,338
What's the matter
with me?

358
00:23:42,421 --> 00:23:44,423
There's nothing the matter with
me. What's the matter with you?

359
00:23:44,506 --> 00:23:46,759
I just don't want to
be insulted. That's all.

360
00:23:46,842 --> 00:23:49,011
You're not
being insulted.

361
00:23:49,094 --> 00:23:50,429
After all, you can't
blame him, can we,

362
00:23:50,512 --> 00:23:53,307
for turning down an old married
couple like us for a girl like that.

363
00:23:53,390 --> 00:23:54,850
We're not an old
married couple!

364
00:23:54,934 --> 00:23:56,936
All right.
All right.

365
00:23:57,019 --> 00:23:59,480
All right, he's a heel.
I don't understand him,

366
00:23:59,563 --> 00:24:02,441
but I'm beginning not to like
what he's doing to our whole night.

367
00:24:02,524 --> 00:24:04,944
I must do
some shopping in the market tomorrow.

368
00:24:05,027 --> 00:24:09,031
I do hope it'll be fine.
Well, not too fine.

369
00:24:09,114 --> 00:24:11,325
Of course, I know that our
English weather is pretty awful,

370
00:24:11,408 --> 00:24:14,411
but sometimes, you know, I think
we don't realize when we're lucky.

371
00:24:14,495 --> 00:24:17,039
All this sunshine
day after day,

372
00:24:17,122 --> 00:24:19,458
well, it doesn't
seem natural somehow.

373
00:24:19,541 --> 00:24:20,501
I want to get up.

374
00:24:20,584 --> 00:24:21,627
Ben, don't.

375
00:24:21,710 --> 00:24:23,629
I know you. Once you get
worked up, you start a fight.

376
00:24:23,712 --> 00:24:25,756
Now, forget about him.

377
00:24:26,590 --> 00:24:29,134
Will you come to the
market with us tomorrow?

378
00:24:29,218 --> 00:24:31,804
As a matter of fact, Louis
Bernard, the big buyer from Paris,

379
00:24:31,887 --> 00:24:33,806
was going to take us to
the marketplace tomorrow.

380
00:24:33,889 --> 00:24:35,683
Yeah. Yeah, I think I'll
go over and cancel out.

381
00:24:35,766 --> 00:24:38,978
Now, Ben, sit down and eat
your dinner. It's getting cold.

382
00:24:39,061 --> 00:24:40,145
We'd love to go.

383
00:24:40,229 --> 00:24:41,939
Good, good.
We'd be delighted.

384
00:24:42,523 --> 00:24:46,235
I don't know why he gets so
worked up over unimportant things.

385
00:24:52,992 --> 00:24:54,243
<i>Monsieur!</i>

386
00:25:57,264 --> 00:25:59,058
What's he saying,
Mrs. Drayton?

387
00:25:59,141 --> 00:26:00,809
He's the teller
of tales, Hank.

388
00:26:04,813 --> 00:26:06,273
Isn't this exciting?

389
00:26:06,356 --> 00:26:08,400
Just like the county
fair when I was a kid.

390
00:26:08,484 --> 00:26:11,445
They got everything but
the balloon ascension.

391
00:26:14,323 --> 00:26:16,617
What's so funny about that? Did
you ever see a balloon ascension?

392
00:26:16,700 --> 00:26:17,785
No, you know what
I was just thinking?

393
00:26:17,868 --> 00:26:19,828
You know what's paying for
these three days in Marrakech?

394
00:26:19,912 --> 00:26:20,913
Me.

395
00:26:20,996 --> 00:26:22,664
Mrs. Campbell's
gallstones.

396
00:26:24,124 --> 00:26:26,168
You know the purse I
bought in Paris? Yeah.

397
00:26:26,251 --> 00:26:28,670
Bill Edward's tonsils.

398
00:26:28,754 --> 00:26:30,422
Mommy! Daddy!

399
00:26:30,506 --> 00:26:34,468
Daddy, come with us! We're
gonna see the medicine man.

400
00:26:34,551 --> 00:26:36,095
Maybe you can learn
something, Daddy.

401
00:26:36,178 --> 00:26:37,805
I wouldn't be
a bit surprised.

402
00:26:37,888 --> 00:26:39,098
Anytime he starts
wearing you out...

403
00:26:39,181 --> 00:26:42,476
I haven't enjoyed
the market so much.

404
00:26:43,685 --> 00:26:45,771
You know, I never
thought of it that way before.

405
00:26:45,854 --> 00:26:46,939
What?

406
00:26:47,022 --> 00:26:49,233
I'm wearing Johnny
Matthews' appendix.

407
00:26:49,316 --> 00:26:52,111
Dear.
What about the boat trip?

408
00:26:52,194 --> 00:26:53,695
Let's see, it took
two boys, one girl

409
00:26:53,779 --> 00:26:55,322
and two sets of twins,
didn't it?

410
00:26:55,405 --> 00:26:56,615
And Mrs. Morgan's
hives.

411
00:27:04,706 --> 00:27:05,874
Well, how are the
acrobats today?

412
00:27:05,958 --> 00:27:06,959
Wonderful.

413
00:27:07,042 --> 00:27:09,628
Watch that kid that goes clear
to the top there. He's great.

414
00:27:09,711 --> 00:27:11,713
I'll see you later.
Yes.

415
00:27:14,883 --> 00:27:18,554
All the way home, we'll be
riding on Herbie Taylor's ulcers.

416
00:27:18,637 --> 00:27:20,889
And AIIida Markle's
asthma.

417
00:27:20,973 --> 00:27:22,558
Now, if we could
just get four cases

418
00:27:22,641 --> 00:27:24,476
of the seven-year itch,
we could retire.

419
00:27:24,560 --> 00:27:26,478
Or if Mrs. Yarro's really
gonna have triplets,

420
00:27:26,562 --> 00:27:28,438
we could completely redecorate
the house, couldn't we?

421
00:27:29,898 --> 00:27:32,317
What would they say
if they heard us?

422
00:27:32,401 --> 00:27:34,862
You know, one of the reasons I
came to a place like Marrakech

423
00:27:34,945 --> 00:27:37,990
is so we could say things like
that Without everybody hearing us.

424
00:27:40,492 --> 00:27:43,328
Well, I'd like to say something
where nobody could hear us.

425
00:27:43,412 --> 00:27:44,872
This is
the safest place.

426
00:27:44,955 --> 00:27:47,583
When are we going
to have another baby?

427
00:27:48,584 --> 00:27:50,878
You're the doctor.
You have all the answers.

428
00:27:50,961 --> 00:27:53,964
Yeah, but this is the first time
I've ever heard the question.

429
00:27:54,047 --> 00:27:56,258
Mommy, look!
Come here!

430
00:28:00,137 --> 00:28:03,974
Look. Sewing machines. Looks
like a television commercial.

431
00:28:05,767 --> 00:28:06,810
Having a good time,
Hank?

432
00:28:06,894 --> 00:28:07,895
I guess so.

433
00:28:07,978 --> 00:28:10,022
He's delighted
with everything.

434
00:28:10,147 --> 00:28:11,607
Coming through! Coming through!

435
00:28:18,363 --> 00:28:19,740
Hank! Hank,
come back here!

436
00:28:19,823 --> 00:28:20,824
Hank!

437
00:28:20,908 --> 00:28:23,035
Hank!
Hank!

438
00:28:23,118 --> 00:28:24,745
It's best to keep
out of trouble, Hank.

439
00:28:24,828 --> 00:28:26,413
What's going on?

440
00:28:26,496 --> 00:28:28,749
Looks like the police
are chasing somebody.

441
00:29:29,393 --> 00:29:31,561
Hey.
Hey, look there.

442
00:29:35,315 --> 00:29:37,359
You better stand back.
Go on. Stand back.

443
00:29:54,084 --> 00:29:55,335
<i>Monsieur</i> McKenna.

444
00:29:57,296 --> 00:30:00,090
I'm Louis Bernard.

445
00:30:06,054 --> 00:30:09,057
A man, a statesman,

446
00:30:10,225 --> 00:30:16,148
he is to be killed,
assassinated, in London.

447
00:30:17,607 --> 00:30:20,068
Soon, very soon.

448
00:30:22,070 --> 00:30:25,282
Tell them in London.

449
00:30:27,617 --> 00:30:30,537
Ambrose Chappell.

450
00:31:00,734 --> 00:31:02,736
Ben, who is he?
Louis Bernard.

451
00:31:02,861 --> 00:31:04,696
You got something to
write on? Louis Bernard?

452
00:31:04,780 --> 00:31:06,448
He's dead.

453
00:31:33,725 --> 00:31:35,310
He says,
"Do you know this man?"

454
00:31:35,394 --> 00:31:38,897
Yes, we do know him.
He's Louis Bernard, the...

455
00:31:38,980 --> 00:31:40,440
Louis Bernard?

456
00:31:42,234 --> 00:31:44,486
<i>Monsieur and
Madame</i> McKenna.

457
00:31:48,365 --> 00:31:50,784
He wants you to go to police
headquarters to make a statement.

458
00:31:50,867 --> 00:31:52,035
Okay.

459
00:31:52,119 --> 00:31:54,162
Our friends have to go
to the police station.

460
00:31:54,287 --> 00:31:56,248
I think I better go with
them. Yes, of course.

461
00:32:03,505 --> 00:32:06,508
You don't want your little boy to
go, do you?

462
00:32:06,591 --> 00:32:09,886
But I
want to go to the police station.

463
00:32:09,970 --> 00:32:12,347
I think it better if I take him
back to the hotel, don't you?

464
00:32:12,431 --> 00:32:13,765
Would you please?
Certainly.

465
00:32:13,849 --> 00:32:16,560
Thank you.
You be a good boy, Hank.

466
00:32:18,186 --> 00:32:20,021
We're to be going now.

467
00:32:20,105 --> 00:32:22,732
Heaven knows when
we shall be back.

468
00:32:28,071 --> 00:32:30,323
Ben, why do you suppose
he turned up in an Arab outfit

469
00:32:30,407 --> 00:32:31,992
and wearing make-up?

470
00:32:32,075 --> 00:32:34,453
What's more important,
why was he killed?

471
00:32:34,536 --> 00:32:36,580
I'll bet he was a spy
or something like that.

472
00:32:36,663 --> 00:32:38,498
What were you writing down?
What was he telling you?

473
00:32:38,582 --> 00:32:40,625
I'll tell you later.

474
00:32:42,627 --> 00:32:43,628
What is it?

475
00:32:43,712 --> 00:32:45,755
I just feel
kind of funny.

476
00:32:47,132 --> 00:32:50,051
Why should he pick
me out to tell?

477
00:32:50,135 --> 00:32:53,513
After what we said about
him last night, the poor fella.

478
00:33:06,234 --> 00:33:07,652
When we get in
with the inspector,

479
00:33:07,736 --> 00:33:09,654
I'll do my best to cut
some of the red tape.

480
00:33:09,738 --> 00:33:11,323
Fine. Fine.

481
00:33:11,448 --> 00:33:13,074
Well, I'm going
to stretch a bit.

482
00:33:14,451 --> 00:33:16,786
I'm afraid the questions
will go on till doomsday

483
00:33:16,870 --> 00:33:19,039
if you admit you knew
this chap Bernard before.

484
00:33:19,122 --> 00:33:21,666
I don't know him at all.
We met yesterday on a bus.

485
00:33:21,750 --> 00:33:23,919
They're a cynical lot,
you know, these French.

486
00:33:24,002 --> 00:33:25,962
They might refuse
to believe that.

487
00:33:26,046 --> 00:33:29,090
Well, they've got to
believe it. It's the truth.

488
00:33:29,174 --> 00:33:31,176
Look at it from
their point of view.

489
00:33:31,259 --> 00:33:33,136
They saw this poor
fellow whispering to you,

490
00:33:33,220 --> 00:33:35,597
and then they saw you
write something down.

491
00:33:35,680 --> 00:33:37,098
Are you gonna show
them what you wrote?

492
00:33:58,078 --> 00:34:01,706
Thank you, Mr. Drayton, but a
translator will not be necessary.

493
00:34:01,790 --> 00:34:04,626
Won't <i>you</i> come inside,
<i>madame, monsieur?</i>

494
00:34:06,127 --> 00:34:07,254
Please do me
the kindness to wait.

495
00:34:07,337 --> 00:34:09,589
I might have questions
for you later.

496
00:34:09,673 --> 00:34:10,715
