00:48:43,045 --> 00:48:47,174
"Tell them in London
to try Ambrose Chappell."

742
00:48:47,633 --> 00:48:49,093
That's the fella
we've got to find.

743
00:48:49,176 --> 00:48:50,594
And if he knows
anything about this,

744
00:48:50,678 --> 00:48:54,098
I'm gonna offer him every
penny I have to get Hank back.

745
00:48:54,181 --> 00:48:57,268
The Chappell guy's our only
hope. You understand that, Jo?

746
00:48:57,351 --> 00:49:00,187
Now, I've got a car
waiting downstairs.

747
00:49:00,271 --> 00:49:04,316
I've paid the hotel bill. We
get packed, we'll be all set.

748
00:49:04,400 --> 00:49:05,860
Honey?

749
00:49:08,070 --> 00:49:13,075
We don't have much time. You'll
have to get up and start getting ready.

750
00:49:13,159 --> 00:49:14,577
Please, Jo.

751
00:49:16,579 --> 00:49:17,788
Please, Jo.

752
00:49:40,644 --> 00:49:42,938
Would you just wait, sir,
for the press photographers?

753
00:49:43,022 --> 00:49:44,356
Will you come
this way, madam?

754
00:49:44,440 --> 00:49:46,817
Jo, darling,
love from the fan club!

755
00:49:48,569 --> 00:49:50,654
How could they
remember me so well, Ben?

756
00:49:50,738 --> 00:49:52,740
It's been four years
since I played London.

757
00:49:52,823 --> 00:49:55,868
You're the kind of gal
they don't forget.

758
00:49:56,660 --> 00:50:00,206
Who told them we were
coming? Ben, you didn't.

759
00:50:00,289 --> 00:50:03,375
All I did was wire your friends,
the Parnells, to get us hotel rooms.

760
00:50:03,459 --> 00:50:05,002
I never figured on
anything like this.

761
00:50:11,800 --> 00:50:13,427
Dr. and Mrs. McKenna,

762
00:50:13,511 --> 00:50:17,056
I'm Inspector Edington of the
Criminal Investigation Department.

763
00:50:17,139 --> 00:50:20,518
As things are, there's no need
for you to go through the Customs.

764
00:50:20,601 --> 00:50:22,228
Come this way.

765
00:50:24,605 --> 00:50:25,940
How about
a photo, Jo?

766
00:50:26,023 --> 00:50:27,316
Hi, Jo!

767
00:50:32,571 --> 00:50:34,323
This way, please.

768
00:50:35,074 --> 00:50:38,577
We want Jo!
We want Jo! We want Jo! We want Jo!

769
00:50:38,661 --> 00:50:40,287
We want Jo! We want Jo!

770
00:50:41,455 --> 00:50:43,707
This is Mr. Woburn.
Dr. and Mrs. McKenna.

771
00:50:43,791 --> 00:50:45,042
How do you do?
How do you do?

772
00:50:45,125 --> 00:50:46,627
What do you people
want with us?

773
00:50:46,710 --> 00:50:48,754
Mr. Buchanan would like to
have a chat with you inside.

774
00:50:48,837 --> 00:50:50,256
Who's Mr. Buchanan?

775
00:50:50,339 --> 00:50:52,591
Special Branch,
Scotland Yard.

776
00:51:01,475 --> 00:51:03,894
This is Mr. Buchanan.
Dr. and Mrs. McKenna.

777
00:51:03,978 --> 00:51:06,522
How do you do?
Thank you, Woburn.

778
00:51:07,273 --> 00:51:09,149
Do sit down,
won't you?

779
00:51:10,818 --> 00:51:12,486
Let me say at once
that we're shocked

780
00:51:12,570 --> 00:51:14,863
that your son was taken
from you in Marrakech,

781
00:51:14,947 --> 00:51:17,199
and deeply sympathetic.

782
00:51:17,283 --> 00:51:18,242
Do you know
where he is?

783
00:51:18,325 --> 00:51:19,743
Have you heard anything
about our boy?

784
00:51:19,827 --> 00:51:22,204
I only wish I could give
you some cheerful news,

785
00:51:22,288 --> 00:51:25,874
but we might find him quite
soon indeed if we work together.

786
00:51:26,834 --> 00:51:29,878
Bernard the Frenchman was
sent to Morocco at our request

787
00:51:29,962 --> 00:51:33,007
to check up on an
assassination plot here in London.

788
00:51:33,090 --> 00:51:37,344
You know, a good agent
keeps on staking his life.

789
00:51:37,428 --> 00:51:38,554
He doesn't always win.

790
00:51:39,013 --> 00:51:41,223
Bernard reckoned you
were a man to trust.

791
00:51:41,348 --> 00:51:43,601
He relied on you
to come to us.

792
00:51:43,684 --> 00:51:47,021
Those people kidnapped your
boy in order to keep your mouth shut.

793
00:51:49,023 --> 00:51:50,357
That's right, isn't it?

794
00:51:51,442 --> 00:51:53,944
No, I think they
took him for money.

795
00:51:54,028 --> 00:51:56,071
Then why didn't you go straight
to your consulate in Casablanca?

796
00:51:56,155 --> 00:51:58,073
Why did you come
to London?

797
00:51:58,157 --> 00:51:59,199
Well, I...

798
00:51:59,283 --> 00:52:00,492
Mr. Buchanan...
No, no.

799
00:52:00,576 --> 00:52:02,620
You're convinced that these
people brought your son to London.

800
00:52:02,703 --> 00:52:05,831
You're convinced that you
can find him off your own bat.

801
00:52:05,914 --> 00:52:08,208
You can't.
It's impossible.

802
00:52:08,709 --> 00:52:11,795
But with the help we can
give you, there's a chance,

803
00:52:11,879 --> 00:52:13,047
a really good chance.

804
00:52:13,130 --> 00:52:15,049
But they told us
not to say anything.

805
00:52:15,132 --> 00:52:18,344
Anything you tell me will be in
the most absolute confidence.

806
00:52:18,427 --> 00:52:20,304
Yes, that may
be true, but...

807
00:52:20,387 --> 00:52:23,307
Your son is the trump
card these people hold.

808
00:52:23,390 --> 00:52:25,267
He's perfectly safe
for the moment.

809
00:52:25,351 --> 00:52:26,810
And when they've
done what they want,

810
00:52:26,894 --> 00:52:28,479
they'll let him go.
Is that the idea?

811
00:52:28,562 --> 00:52:30,481
Are we supposed to
just sit here and wait?

812
00:52:30,564 --> 00:52:31,940
No, Mrs. McKenna.

813
00:52:32,024 --> 00:52:36,820
If they consider your boy a
nuisance afterwards, I'm afraid...

814
00:52:36,904 --> 00:52:40,157
There's no need for you to
try and scare us, Mr. Buchanan.

815
00:52:40,240 --> 00:52:43,410
That's exactly what I am
trying to do, scare you.

816
00:52:44,203 --> 00:52:48,123
I'm trying to prevent a man
being murdered here in London.

817
00:52:48,207 --> 00:52:50,209
If you don't tell
me all you know,

818
00:52:50,292 --> 00:52:53,128
you become an accessory
before the fact of murder.

819
00:52:53,212 --> 00:52:55,297
Ben, what can we
do by ourselves?

820
00:52:55,381 --> 00:52:57,675
Now, wait a minute.
Now, wait just a minute.

821
00:52:57,758 --> 00:52:59,510
You've been working
on the wrong McKenna.

822
00:52:59,593 --> 00:53:02,388
Louis Bernard talked to me. He
didn't talk to my Wife, you know.

823
00:53:02,471 --> 00:53:03,555
Then you tell me.

824
00:53:03,639 --> 00:53:05,516
He was a Frenchman.
He spoke to me in French,

825
00:53:05,599 --> 00:53:08,477
and I don't understand a
single word of the language!

826
00:53:08,560 --> 00:53:10,562
Ben, maybe they could
find those people and Hank.

827
00:53:10,646 --> 00:53:12,523
Maybe. Maybe's not
good enough for me.

828
00:53:12,606 --> 00:53:14,400
And I don't think it ought to
be good enough for you either.

829
00:53:14,483 --> 00:53:16,193
You act as if you're the only
one who's concerned about...

830
00:53:16,276 --> 00:53:17,861
Honey, honey, I
didn't mean it that way.

831
00:53:17,945 --> 00:53:20,322
We made up our minds what
we're gonna do about this thing.

832
00:53:20,406 --> 00:53:23,200
Now let's try
and stick to it.

833
00:53:23,784 --> 00:53:26,662
I'm sorry,
Mr. Buchanan,

834
00:53:26,745 --> 00:53:30,874
we'd like to cooperate with you
on this thing, but we just can't.

835
00:53:31,333 --> 00:53:33,419
Well,
I've got a son of my own.

836
00:53:34,878 --> 00:53:35,921
I don't know What I'd do.

837
00:53:37,256 --> 00:53:38,674
Excuse me.

838
00:53:47,099 --> 00:53:49,727
Telephone call for you,
Mrs. McKenna.

839
00:53:51,687 --> 00:53:55,566
Put the telephone call for Mrs.
McKenna through here, please.

840
00:54:02,614 --> 00:54:03,615
Hello.

841
00:54:03,699 --> 00:54:04,783
<i><i>Mrs. McKenna?</i></i>

842
00:54:04,867 --> 00:54:06,076
Yes?

843
00:54:06,160 --> 00:54:08,954
<i>This is Mrs. Drayton.
Do you remember me?</i>

844
00:54:09,413 --> 00:54:11,331
Mrs. Drayton.

845
00:54:11,915 --> 00:54:14,209
Where is our son?
Where have you got him?

846
00:54:16,879 --> 00:54:21,008
<i>He's here with me. You
mustn't worry about him, really.</i>

847
00:54:21,091 --> 00:54:23,218
Where's our son?
Where have you got him?

848
00:54:23,302 --> 00:54:25,721
<i>I expect you'd like to
speak to him, wouldn't you?</i>

849
00:54:25,804 --> 00:54:28,015
Yes, please! Please.

850
00:54:30,225 --> 00:54:32,144
Hank! Hello, Hank!

851
00:54:32,227 --> 00:54:33,812
<i>Just a minute.</i>

852
00:54:38,192 --> 00:54:40,736
<i>Mommy?
Mommy, is that you?</i>

853
00:54:40,819 --> 00:54:43,530
Hank, darling,
are you really all right?

854
00:54:44,490 --> 00:54:49,286
<i>I'm a little scared, Mommy,
but I'm all right, I guess.</i>

855
00:54:49,369 --> 00:54:52,706
<i>I miss you, Mommy.
I miss you so much!</i>

856
00:54:53,999 --> 00:54:57,961
Here. Hank. Hank, this
is Daddy.

857
00:54:58,045 --> 00:54:59,463
<i>Is Mommy crying?</i>

858
00:54:59,546 --> 00:55:01,256
Now, Hank, listen to me.

859
00:55:01,340 --> 00:55:04,551
Where are you?
Where are you?

860
00:55:05,844 --> 00:55:08,180
<i>I didn't mean to
make her cry, Daddy,</i>

861
00:55:08,263 --> 00:55:11,058
<i>but I'm scared,
and I want to see her.</i>

862
00:55:11,141 --> 00:55:15,479
Hank, son, now listen. Tell me
where you are. Where are you?

863
00:55:17,272 --> 00:55:18,482
<i>Welbeck eight...</i>

864
00:55:18,607 --> 00:55:19,817
Yeah?

865
00:55:21,109 --> 00:55:22,402
Eight. Go on, Hank.

866
00:55:23,821 --> 00:55:25,113
Hank!

867
00:55:38,377 --> 00:55:40,462
Ben, he was so scared.

868
00:55:47,177 --> 00:55:49,680
It was a London
telephone exchange.

869
00:55:49,763 --> 00:55:51,890
Public call box.
West One.

870
00:55:52,766 --> 00:55:56,395
Do I have to say any
more? Come on, dear.

871
00:55:56,478 --> 00:55:58,564
You may change
your minds.

872
00:56:00,148 --> 00:56:01,483
If you do,

873
00:56:03,777 --> 00:56:05,779
this number
will find me.

874
00:56:11,577 --> 00:56:15,998
<i>Baggage and
airport service for 552 from Paris...</i>

875
00:56:24,464 --> 00:56:26,383
Everything all right,
sir? Yeah, yeah.

876
00:56:26,466 --> 00:56:28,343
Your room key, sir.
Thank you.

877
00:56:28,427 --> 00:56:30,971
Here.

878
00:56:31,054 --> 00:56:33,223
Thank you, sir.
There you are.

879
00:56:33,307 --> 00:56:36,393
It's from the Parnells.
"Welcome home, Jo.

880
00:56:36,476 --> 00:56:40,522
"Look forward to seeing your
family, especially the little one."

881
00:56:51,742 --> 00:56:54,953
"With love, from Jan and
Cindy." That's very nice.

882
00:57:02,836 --> 00:57:05,756
"Ambrose Chappell."
There he is, big as life.

883
00:57:05,839 --> 00:57:12,471
"61 Burdett Street, Camden
Town. Gulliver 6198."

884
00:57:13,138 --> 00:57:14,473
What are you
going to say?

885
00:57:14,556 --> 00:57:16,433
I'm gonna tell him
I'll keep my mouth shut

886
00:57:16,516 --> 00:57:19,478
and offer him all the
money we have for Hank.

887
00:57:20,270 --> 00:57:21,647
Operator?

888
00:57:22,856 --> 00:57:27,319
Operator,
I want Gulliver 6198.

889
00:57:29,112 --> 00:57:30,572
|'|| get it.

890
00:57:33,533 --> 00:57:36,036
Jo! You look wonderful!
Jo!

891
00:57:36,119 --> 00:57:37,913
When we got your Wire,
I couldn't believe it.

892
00:57:37,996 --> 00:57:39,456
What were you doing
down in Morocco?

893
00:57:39,539 --> 00:57:40,624
Sightseeing.

894
00:57:40,707 --> 00:57:42,834
You're the perfect answer
to what London needs, Jo.

895
00:57:42,918 --> 00:57:45,045
This week's the dullest
thing since my first show.

896
00:57:45,128 --> 00:57:47,130
Ambrose Chappell.

897
00:57:47,214 --> 00:57:48,840
Mr. Ambrose Chappell.

898
00:57:48,924 --> 00:57:51,218
Mr. Conway, I didn't
know you were there.

899
00:57:51,301 --> 00:57:54,680
Dr. McKenna. Dr. McKenna.
Welcome to London town, Doctor.

900
00:57:54,763 --> 00:57:58,100
I am sorry. I knew you were
married. But a doctor? How clever.

901
00:57:58,183 --> 00:58:00,310
Especially in such
a psychosomatic business.

902
00:58:00,394 --> 00:58:02,521
Jan, will you
keep quiet?

903
00:58:02,604 --> 00:58:04,690
Honey, you wouldn't know
what psychosomatic means.

904
00:58:04,773 --> 00:58:06,483
I do too. It means when your
mind gets sick of your body,

905
00:58:06,566 --> 00:58:08,026
it does something to it.

906
00:58:08,110 --> 00:58:10,112
Can't you see the
doctor's trying to telephone?

907
00:58:10,195 --> 00:58:12,781
Not at all. It's just some
business. It's nothing.

908
00:58:12,864 --> 00:58:15,283
Business is everything.
Shh!

909
00:58:15,867 --> 00:58:19,454
Hello. Hello?
Ambrose Chappell.

910
00:58:19,955 --> 00:58:22,457
I say, is this
Mr. Ambrose Chappell?

911
00:58:23,041 --> 00:58:26,837
Well, my name's McKenna.
Dr. Benjamin McKenna.

912
00:58:29,798 --> 00:58:32,259
I don't think we need to be
quiet. Would you like a drink?

913
00:58:32,342 --> 00:58:36,471
I was wondering if you'd be at
your address for a little while.

914
00:58:36,555 --> 00:58:38,348
I'd like to speak to
you for a few minutes.

915
00:58:38,432 --> 00:58:41,059
Yes. Thank you.
I'll be right over.

916
00:58:43,437 --> 00:58:45,105
I'd like all of you
to meet my husband.

917
00:58:45,188 --> 00:58:46,690
I've heard so much
about you, Doctor.

918
00:58:46,773 --> 00:58:48,066
It's nice to
see you in person.

919
00:58:48,150 --> 00:58:49,943
How do you do, sir?
This is Val's wife, Helen.

920
00:58:50,027 --> 00:58:51,028
How do you do?

921
00:58:51,111 --> 00:58:52,362
You look just
like those pictures

922
00:58:52,446 --> 00:58:54,448
Jo had in her dressing
room four years ago.

923
00:58:54,531 --> 00:58:55,615
Haven't changed a bit.

924
00:58:55,699 --> 00:58:56,742
Why should he?
He's a doctor.

925
00:58:56,825 --> 00:58:57,909
Probably gets
free hormones.

926
00:58:57,993 --> 00:58:59,036
Yes.

927
00:58:59,119 --> 00:59:01,705
I'm Jan Peterson. I sing
almost as well as your wife.

928
00:59:03,081 --> 00:59:06,043
And, darling, this is Cindy
Fontaine from Harrisburg, PA.

929
00:59:06,126 --> 00:59:08,837
Harrisburg.
Been back home lately?

930
00:59:08,920 --> 00:59:11,715
How can I? They know
me there as Elva McDuff.

931
00:59:11,840 --> 00:59:13,633
It doesn't quite fit me
anymore.

932
00:59:13,717 --> 00:59:16,678
Where's your boy? I'd like to
see which one of you he looks like.

933
00:59:16,762 --> 00:59:18,180
He's staying with
some other people

934
00:59:18,263 --> 00:59:20,724
so we could have a
little time by ourselves.

935
00:59:20,807 --> 00:59:22,225
What's his name?

936
00:59:22,309 --> 00:59:24,186
Hank.
Henry, really.

937
00:59:24,269 --> 00:59:27,314
Well, I hope he looks
like you and has the doctor's brain.

938
00:59:28,899 --> 00:59:31,234
These flowers are really so
lovely. We thank you very much.

939
00:59:31,318 --> 00:59:33,153
Well, I'll order
some drinks.

940
00:59:33,236 --> 00:59:34,738
Okay, but dinner
tonight's on me,

941
00:59:34,821 --> 00:59:36,406
a sort of welcome
home for Jo.

942
00:59:36,490 --> 00:59:38,200
I wish I could persuade
her to stay a month.

943
00:59:38,283 --> 00:59:39,826
I wish I could,
Val, but I can't.

944
00:59:39,910 --> 00:59:42,788
I'm terribly sorry, but I have
an appointment I have to keep.

945
00:59:42,871 --> 00:59:44,873
I wonder if you'd order
the drinks, Mr. Parnell.

946
00:59:44,956 --> 00:59:48,210
I'll be back as soon as I
can. Excuse me, please.

947
00:59:48,293 --> 00:59:49,336
Ben, please.

948
00:59:49,961 --> 00:59:51,755
Ben, please.
It's got to be done.

949
00:59:51,838 --> 00:59:52,923
Take me with you.

950
00:59:53,006 --> 00:59:54,758
No, no, no. I can't.
I won't disappear.

951
00:59:54,841 --> 00:59:57,385
For the last time,
please let me go with you.

952
00:59:57,469 --> 00:59:59,262
Honey, two people are
easier to follow than one.

953
00:59:59,346 --> 01:00:00,889
Now we don't want
Buchanan's men on our tracks,

954
01:00:00,972 --> 01:00:02,140
the other people either.

955
01:00:02,224 --> 01:00:05,644
I'm going out through
the service entrance.

956
01:02:57,023 --> 01:02:58,316
Yes, sir?
Ambrose Chappell?

957
01:02:58,400 --> 01:02:59,651
Come in.

958
01:03:07,367 --> 01:03:09,869
There's a gent
to see you, sir.

959
01:03:17,502 --> 01:03:22,465
Good afternoon, sir. I am Ambrose
Chappell. What can I do for you?

960
01:03:23,216 --> 01:03:25,218
Well, I...

961
01:03:25,302 --> 01:03:27,887
If you gave me your name,
that might be a start.

962
01:03:27,971 --> 01:03:32,726
Yes, of course. My name is
McKenna. Dr. Benjamin McKenna.

963
01:03:32,809 --> 01:03:33,810
I phoned you.

964
01:03:33,893 --> 01:03:34,936
Yes, yes.

965
01:03:37,230 --> 01:03:38,690
You are Ambrose Chappell?

966
01:03:39,399 --> 01:03:43,028
Well, I've been Ambrose
Chappell for nearly 71 years.

967
01:03:44,404 --> 01:03:46,239
But I think I understand
your problem.

968
01:03:46,323 --> 01:03:47,949
You do?
Certainly.

969
01:03:48,033 --> 01:03:49,951
It happens all the time.

970
01:03:50,410 --> 01:03:51,828
You expected
someone else.

971
01:03:52,412 --> 01:03:54,664
Just a moment.
Ambrose?

972
01:03:59,002 --> 01:04:01,880
I think this gentleman
wants to talk to us.

973
01:04:07,719 --> 01:04:10,847
Now, Father, why don't
you go and have a nice rest?

974
01:04:12,098 --> 01:04:14,642
I have centuries of rest
ahead of me, thank you.

975
01:04:14,726 --> 01:04:16,478
Good day to you, sir.

976
01:04:17,896 --> 01:04:19,272
Now, what can
I do for you?

977
01:04:19,356 --> 01:04:20,732
I'm Dr. McKenna.

978
01:04:22,984 --> 01:04:24,194
That name mean
anything to you?

979
01:04:24,778 --> 01:04:27,113
No. No, I don't think so.

980
01:04:28,031 --> 01:04:29,574
You've no idea
why I'm here?

981
01:04:32,118 --> 01:04:34,871
My dear sir,
Ihaven%the faintest idea.

982
01:04:34,954 --> 01:04:36,414
But your name
was given to me

983
01:04:36,498 --> 01:04:39,250
by someone I happened
to meet in Marrakech.

984
01:04:40,335 --> 01:04:42,003
Yes?
Yes.

985
01:04:42,087 --> 01:04:46,925
Now, I think you know this man,
Louis Bernard, a Frenchman.

986
01:04:47,592 --> 01:04:48,676
Louis Bernard?

987
01:04:49,636 --> 01:04:51,096
Come on. Let's stop
fooling around.

988
01:04:51,179 --> 01:04:53,848
Bernard told me to come
here just before he died.

989
01:04:54,808 --> 01:04:57,852
This man is dead?

990
01:04:57,936 --> 01:04:59,813
You know he's dead
just as well as I do.

991
01:04:59,896 --> 01:05:01,815
Now, I've come here with
a business proposition.

992
01:05:01,898 --> 01:05:04,526
I don't see how you
can turn it down.

993
01:05:10,740 --> 01:05:12,909
Exactly What
had you in mind?

994
01:05:14,828 --> 01:05:15,995
You want to talk here?

995
01:05:16,162 --> 01:05:17,247
Certainly.

996
01:05:17,330 --> 01:05:19,749
We have no secrets
from our employees.

997
01:05:20,583 --> 01:05:22,585
Okay. Now,
in the first place,

998
01:05:22,669 --> 01:05:25,922
I haven't uttered one word of
what Bernard told me before he died,

999
01:05:26,005 --> 01:05:27,048
and I never will.

1000
01:05:27,132 --> 01:05:30,135
Frankly, I'm not interested
in political intrigue.

1001
01:05:30,218 --> 01:05:33,012
I don't care who you fellows
are gonna kill here in London.

1002
01:05:33,096 --> 01:05:34,514
All I want is that boy,

1003
01:05:34,597 --> 01:05:37,267
and I'll take the next
airplane back to America.

1004
01:05:37,684 --> 01:05:40,437
Come on, please.
Listen to me, will you?

1005
01:05:40,520 --> 01:05:43,940
Honestly, if money means
anything to you, I'll do...

1006
01:05:44,023 --> 01:05:45,984
Father,
call the police quick.

1007
01:05:46,067 --> 01:05:48,278
Now, sir, I shall we go into
this a little more carefully...

1008
01:05:48,361 --> 01:05:49,404
Wait just a minute.

1009
01:05:49,529 --> 01:05:51,489
You told him to call the
police. No, no. No, no.

1010
01:05:51,573 --> 01:05:53,074
What's the idea,
trying to bluff me?

1011
01:05:53,158 --> 01:05:55,118
My dear sir,
there can be no...

1012
01:05:55,201 --> 01:05:56,286
Let me go.

1013
01:05:56,369 --> 01:05:57,370
Are you sure you don't
know Louis Bernard?

1014
01:05:57,454 --> 01:05:58,455
I've never
heard of him.

1015
01:05:58,538 --> 01:05:59,873
You've got no idea
what happened yesterday

1016
01:05:59,956 --> 01:06:01,958
in Marrakech or
where my boy is?

1017
01:06:02,041 --> 01:06:03,251
Of course not.
Where is he?

1018
01:06:03,334 --> 01:06:05,670
William! Edgar!
Davis! Help!

1019
01:06:07,630 --> 01:06:10,300
Now, wait a minute! Wait! All
right, now, hold on. Wait. Listen.

1020
01:06:10,383 --> 01:06:12,135
It's obvious I'm
in the wrong place.

1021
01:06:12,218 --> 01:06:14,804
Now, all right, let
go of me. Come on.

1022
01:06:17,432 --> 01:06:19,017
Come on. Listen.

1023
01:06:22,145 --> 01:06:23,229
Wait.

1024
01:06:25,231 --> 01:06:26,483
Come on.

1025
01:06:28,443 --> 01:06:31,070
I made a mistake.
Now let me go.

1026
01:06:39,787 --> 01:06:41,414
Hold him! Hold him!

1027
01:06:41,498 --> 01:06:43,583
The police are coming.

1028
01:06:49,130 --> 01:06:50,423
Hold him.

1029
01:06:56,262 --> 01:06:56,304
He said that no matter how
Bud Flanagan was got up,

1030
01:06:56,304 --> 01:06:58,973
He said that no matter how
Bud Flanagan was got up,

1031
01:06:59,057 --> 01:07:00,350
even if he was
dressed by Hartnell,

1032
01:07:00,433 --> 01:07:03,102
that nobody would ever
believe that he was an aristocrat.

1033
01:07:03,186 --> 01:07:04,521
So I said,

1034
01:07:04,604 --> 01:07:05,980
"Listen, Chris,

1035
01:07:06,064 --> 01:07:09,567
"why don't you take William
Hickey's column out of the paper?"

1036
01:07:09,651 --> 01:07:13,279
Jo? Jo, what's become of that
unpredictable husband of yours?

1037
01:07:13,363 --> 01:07:15,198
He's been gone
over an hour now.

1038
01:07:15,281 --> 01:07:17,575
He went to see some man.
What was it? Church?

1039
01:07:18,034 --> 01:07:20,119
No. No, it was Chappell.

1040
01:07:27,627 --> 01:07:30,129
It's not a man.
It's a place.

1041
01:07:34,050 --> 01:07:35,843
It's Ambrose Chapel!

1042
01:07:36,553 --> 01:07:38,304
Val, do they list
chapels in the directory?

1043
01:07:38,388 --> 01:07:39,389
Let's take a look.

1044
01:07:39,472 --> 01:07:41,391
Please help me find it.

1045
01:07:42,267 --> 01:07:47,313
Let's see. Here we are.
Ambrose. Here we have a chap...

1046
01:07:47,397 --> 01:07:50,567
Ambrose Chapel,
17 Ambrose Street West Two.

1047
01:07:50,650 --> 01:07:52,193
17 Ambrose Street,
West Two.

1048
01:07:52,277 --> 01:07:54,112
17 Ambrose Street,
West Two.

1049
01:07:55,363 --> 01:07:56,990
17 Ambrose Street.

1050
01:08:00,159 --> 01:08:02,620
Look, darlings, I have
to go. I'm very sorry.

1051
01:08:02,704 --> 01:08:05,290
Have another drink, and
I'll be back as soon as I can.

1052
01:08:05,373 --> 01:08:08,001
And explain to Ben when
he comes in, would you?

1053
01:08:08,126 --> 01:08:09,335
Explain what?
Explain what?

1054
01:08:25,852 --> 01:08:27,478
Look, there's something
weird going on here,

1055
01:08:27,562 --> 01:08:28,605
and I can't
quite follow it.

1056
01:08:28,688 --> 01:08:30,106
Let's try to figure
the whole thing out.

1057
01:08:30,189 --> 01:08:31,608
First of all, there
was a man named...

1058
01:08:31,691 --> 01:08:32,692
Ambrose Chappell.

1059
01:08:32,775 --> 01:08:34,235
And Ben dashed
off to see him.

1060
01:08:34,319 --> 01:08:37,280
Then Jo said it wasn't a man
but a place, and she dashed off.

1061
01:08:37,363 --> 01:08:40,658
Don't mention it again,
darling, or I might dash off.

1062
01:08:40,783 --> 01:08:42,702
Ooh! What a temptation.
Can you fathom it, though?

1063
01:08:42,785 --> 01:08:44,454
It's probably some
new American gag.

1064
01:08:44,537 --> 01:08:45,997
I'll have to ask
Danny about it.

1065
01:08:48,625 --> 01:08:50,293
Well, hello again.

1066
01:08:51,878 --> 01:08:53,630
I'm awfully sorry
I had to rush off,

1067
01:08:53,713 --> 01:08:55,381
but it was something
that had to be done.

1068
01:08:55,465 --> 01:08:57,592
Boy,
I can use this.

1069
01:08:58,593 --> 01:09:01,471
Thank you.
Well, I...

1070
01:09:02,138 --> 01:09:04,015
Where's Jo? She's
gone to Ambrose Chapel.

1071
01:09:04,098 --> 01:09:05,475
I just came
from there.

1072
01:09:05,558 --> 01:09:06,934
Hey, not your
Ambrose Chappell.

1073
01:09:07,018 --> 01:09:09,812
It isn't a he. It's
an it, a building.

1074
01:09:09,896 --> 01:09:12,440
She just left
20 minutes ago.

1075
01:09:12,523 --> 01:09:14,025
She... What?

1076
01:09:15,234 --> 01:09:17,487
What do you mean?
Where's the address?

1077
01:09:17,570 --> 01:09:19,155
I'll look it up again.

1078
01:09:20,156 --> 01:09:22,617
What is this? You
say it's a building?

1079
01:09:22,700 --> 01:09:24,327
Yes, here it is.
Ambrose Chapel,

1080
01:09:24,410 --> 01:09:26,329
17 Ambrose Street,
Bayswater.

1081
01:09:26,412 --> 01:09:28,164
17 Ambrose Street,
Bayswater.

1082
01:09:31,626 --> 01:09:35,088
Yes? Doctor! Doctor,
come back! It's Jo.

1083
01:09:39,634 --> 01:09:41,010
Jo?
Ben?

1084
01:09:41,094 --> 01:09:42,428
What happened?
Did you find anything?

1085
01:09:42,512 --> 01:09:44,305
No, it was
a wild goose chase.

1086
01:09:44,931 --> 01:09:47,558
Darling, it must be
the chapel. I've found it.

1087
01:09:47,642 --> 01:09:48,851
<i>It's just
a short way from here.</i>

1088
01:09:48,935 --> 01:09:50,603
<i>I know it was crazy
thing to do, but...</i>

1089
01:09:50,687 --> 01:09:53,356
Honey, I know the address.
You wait there. I'll be right over.

1090
01:09:53,439 --> 01:09:54,691
All right,
I'll meet you outside.

1091
01:09:54,774 --> 01:09:56,150
<i>Bye, dear.</i>

1092
01:09:56,234 --> 01:09:57,276
What did you say
that address was again?

1093
01:09:57,360 --> 01:09:59,570
17 Ambrose Street,
Bayswater.

1094
01:10:00,488 --> 01:10:02,448
I don't know
how to thank you.

1095
01:10:59,964 --> 01:11:03,676
Three men. You don't know
much about checkers, do you?

1096
01:11:03,760 --> 01:11:06,763
You'd better go to bed, dear,
or you'll be overtired.

1097
01:11:07,263 --> 01:11:08,848
Can I finish?
I'm winning.

1098
01:11:09,474 --> 01:11:10,516
Yes, finish.

1099
01:11:11,350 --> 01:11:13,102
Edna, see he has
some milk and biscuits.

1100
01:11:13,186 --> 01:11:16,230
He'd better be put to sleep again,
honey. I've got to get downstairs.

1101
01:11:16,314 --> 01:11:18,941
No, it's not necessary
tonight.

1102
01:11:19,025 --> 01:11:20,693
You'll sleep, Hank,
won't you?

1103
01:11:20,818 --> 01:11:22,445
I guess so.

1104
01:11:22,528 --> 01:11:24,655
Hurry up if you want
to finish this game.

1105
01:11:24,739 --> 01:11:27,784
Look, it doesn't hurt
to be kind, does it?

1106
01:11:29,702 --> 01:11:33,039
Give me a yell when you
want me to unlock the door.

1107
01:11:43,800 --> 01:11:45,718
- Can I come in?
- Yes.

1108
01:12:13,120 --> 01:12:14,789
I wish it was
tomorrow.

1109
01:12:14,872 --> 01:12:17,875
That's not a very
orthodox sentiment.

1110
01:12:20,711 --> 01:12:22,463
Before I forget.

1111
01:12:23,464 --> 01:12:25,007
Here you are,
my friend.

1112
01:12:25,091 --> 01:12:30,012
Two tickets for the concert at the
Albert Hall with my compliments.

1113
01:12:30,096 --> 01:12:32,265
Your box is
nicely placed.

1114
01:12:32,348 --> 01:12:35,101
Or should we say,
strategically placed.

1115
01:12:35,852 --> 01:12:37,436
And now, for the
most important part.

1116
01:12:37,520 --> 01:12:38,813
What is it?

1117
01:12:38,896 --> 01:12:40,648
A record of
the delightful piece

1118
01:12:40,731 --> 01:12:42,024
they're going to
play this evening.

1119
01:12:42,108 --> 01:12:45,152
Music's less in your
line than marksmanship.

1120
01:12:46,362 --> 01:12:47,947
If you listen,
I'm going to play you

1121
01:12:48,030 --> 01:12:50,616
the exact moment at
which you can shoot.

1122
01:12:50,700 --> 01:12:52,451
So listen carefully.

1123
01:13:02,461 --> 01:13:06,465
We'll have it once more. Listen
for the crash of the cymbals.

1124
01:13:19,353 --> 01:13:21,314
You see?
At such a moment,

1125
01:13:21,397 --> 01:13:22,940
your shot will
never be heard.

1126
01:13:23,858 --> 01:13:26,235
Even the listeners
will be undisturbed.

1127
01:13:26,319 --> 01:13:29,697
I think the composer would've
appreciated that, don't you?

1128
01:13:29,780 --> 01:13:31,616
No one will know.

1129
01:13:31,699 --> 01:13:34,410
No one except one.

1130
01:13:34,493 --> 01:13:37,246
That's right. If you're
clever, my friend.

1131
01:13:38,247 --> 01:13:40,541
Now, any questions,
musical or otherwise?

1132
01:13:40,625 --> 01:13:41,751
No.

1133
01:13:41,834 --> 01:13:43,419
There's one
comforting thought.

1134
01:13:43,502 --> 01:13:45,671
It happens early
in the evening.

1135
01:13:45,755 --> 01:13:47,298
And I hope
I shan't upset you

1136
01:13:47,381 --> 01:13:50,468
if I tell you you've
only time for one shot.

1137
01:13:50,551 --> 01:13:52,345
If you need another,
the risk is yours.

1138
01:13:52,428 --> 01:13:54,180
I don't take risks.

1139
01:13:54,263 --> 01:13:55,681
I'm very glad
to hear that.

1140
01:13:55,765 --> 01:13:58,184
Traipsing all the way
to Marrakech for you,

1141
01:13:58,267 --> 01:13:59,852
I should like you
to do me credit.

1142
01:14:01,354 --> 01:14:03,314
Your distinguished target
is already on his way.

1143
01:14:03,397 --> 01:14:06,859
There's a car waiting for you
downstairs in the back entrance.

1144
01:14:07,526 --> 01:14:09,570
You're to pick up
a Miss Benson on the way.

1145
01:14:09,654 --> 01:14:12,281
She'll be your
companion in the box.

1146
01:14:12,365 --> 01:14:16,118
She'll lend you an air of
respectability if that's possible.

1147
01:14:17,244 --> 01:14:19,956
Will you have
the money when I return?

1148
01:14:21,707 --> 01:14:22,875
Don't you trust me?

1149
01:14:24,585 --> 01:14:26,754
What is your
English proverb?

1150
01:14:26,837 --> 01:14:29,507
"A wolf in
sheep's clothing."

1151
01:14:30,466 --> 01:14:33,427
A very clever disguise,
I must say.

1152
01:14:34,303 --> 01:14:38,516
I think you'd better be going. It's
impolite to be late for a concert.

1153
01:14:39,141 --> 01:14:44,146
And it would be awkward if they made
you wait until the first item was over.

1154
01:14:44,230 --> 01:14:46,482
Will you show our friend
down to the car, my dear?

1155
01:14:46,565 --> 01:14:47,817
Yes, of course.

1156
01:14:47,900 --> 01:14:49,860
I'm sorry you have to
sneak out by the back way,

1157
01:14:49,944 --> 01:14:53,072
but we must preserve
a respectable front.

1158
01:15:45,082 --> 01:15:46,125
There it is.

1159
01:15:48,586 --> 01:15:52,882
Yeah. You just may have
hit it right on the nose.

1160
01:15:52,965 --> 01:15:55,926
And you can't be farther wrong
than I was with my Ambrose Chappell.

1161
01:15:56,010 --> 01:15:57,178
Come on, let's go.

1162
01:15:57,261 --> 01:15:59,055
Ben, should we get
some help from the police?

1163
01:15:59,138 --> 01:16:03,059
No, honey, please. Let's take
a crack at this alone. Come on.

1164
01:17:01,117 --> 01:17:02,743
Ben.
Shh, shh.

1165
01:17:12,211 --> 01:17:18,175
<i>This is just
another wild goose chase</i>

1166
01:17:19,677 --> 01:17:21,637
<i>Let's wait</i>

1167
01:17:22,221 --> 01:17:26,892
<i>And look around</i>

1168
01:17:32,857 --> 01:17:39,613
<i>Look who's coming
down the aisle</i>

1169
01:19:19,171 --> 01:19:23,092
The subject of my address to
you this evening is adversity.

1170
01:19:24,385 --> 01:19:27,137
The average life,
yours and mine,

1171
01:19:27,263 --> 01:19:30,015
is often harassed
and perplexed

1172
01:19:30,099 --> 01:19:34,937
by disappointments and by
cruelties beyond our control.

1173
01:19:35,688 --> 01:19:40,442
Now, strangely enough, it is often
these things beyond our control...

1174
01:19:40,526 --> 01:19:42,945
That's
Buchanan's phone number.

1175
01:19:43,028 --> 01:19:47,241
You go out, call him up, tell him
to surround this place with police.

1176
01:19:47,324 --> 01:19:48,284
What if he asks...

1177
01:19:48,367 --> 01:19:50,244
Tell him anything.

1178
01:19:51,620 --> 01:19:55,040
This is the time. I'm sure
Hank's around here someplace.

1179
01:19:57,459 --> 01:19:59,211
But I don't want to
leave you. I know. I know.

1180
01:19:59,295 --> 01:20:03,590
I don't know how else to
do it, honey. You go on now.

1181
01:20:08,595 --> 01:20:11,807
...and therefore the
goodness of all mankind.

1182
01:20:21,608 --> 01:20:26,196
Few of us pause to consider how
life's adversities work in our behalf

1183
01:20:26,280 --> 01:20:28,824
to make better
men and women of us.

1184
01:20:28,907 --> 01:20:32,161
But I think we should
pause, and pause now,

1185
01:20:32,244 --> 01:20:34,830
to do a little
stocktaking,

1186
01:20:34,913 --> 01:20:38,917
to look into our own hearts and
lives and see what we find there.

1187
01:20:41,086 --> 01:20:44,089
Therefore, instead of
continuing the service,

1188
01:20:44,173 --> 01:20:48,802
I think we should all return to
our homes for private meditation,

1189
01:20:48,886 --> 01:20:51,722
remembering how little
we have to complain of

1190
01:20:51,805 --> 01:20:54,558
and how much to
be grateful for.

1191
01:20:54,641 --> 01:20:58,687
Next week, I shall discuss
the fruits of our meditations.

1192
01:20:58,771 --> 01:21:02,691
Until then, my blessing upon
each and every one of you.

1193
01:22:09,174 --> 01:22:11,677
Well, this is a pleasant
surprise, Doctor.

1194
01:22:12,344 --> 01:22:13,929
Where's my boy,
Drayton?

1195
01:22:14,012 --> 01:22:15,556
He's upstairs.

1196
01:22:15,639 --> 01:22:18,767
As a matter of fact, you've come just
in time to help my wife with his food.

1197
01:22:18,851 --> 01:22:22,563
It seems Hank doesn't care
very much for our English cooking.

1198
01:22:22,646 --> 01:22:24,106
What do you want?

1199
01:22:24,189 --> 01:22:27,818
I'll give you money. I'll keep my
mouth shut. All I want is my boy.

1200
01:22:28,444 --> 01:22:29,987
And what about
your wife?

1201
01:22:30,070 --> 01:22:33,031
Did she go outside just
to get a breath of fresh air?

1202
01:22:33,115 --> 01:22:35,451
Come on. Tell me what
you want. I'll do anything.

1203
01:22:35,534 --> 01:22:39,455
All right, you'll see
your boy all in good time.

1204
01:22:39,997 --> 01:22:43,000
Hank! Hank McKenna!

1205
01:22:44,209 --> 01:22:47,588
Daddy?
Daddy! Daddy! Daddy!

1206
01:22:47,671 --> 01:22:50,549
I'm here, Daddy! I'm here!

1207
01:23:06,857 --> 01:23:10,110
My husband's in there now watching
them. He sent me out to call you

1208
01:23:10,194 --> 01:23:12,362
so that you could do something
before they get away.

1209
01:23:12,446 --> 01:23:14,406
I'm afraid it isn't quite
as easy as all that.

1210
01:23:14,490 --> 01:23:16,658
Mr. Woburn,
my husband is in that chapel

1211
01:23:16,742 --> 01:23:19,328
waiting for me to
bring help. Now you...

1212
01:23:19,411 --> 01:23:21,079
May I speak to
Mr. Buchanan?

1213
01:23:21,163 --> 01:23:23,874
He told me to call him if I needed
him, and I need him right now.

1214
01:23:23,957 --> 01:23:27,002
I'm awfully sorry. But I simply
can't get in touch with him just now.

1215
01:23:27,085 --> 01:23:30,088
He's gone to a rather important
diplomatic affair at the Albert Hall.

1216
01:23:30,172 --> 01:23:32,466
Well, then call him there!
Please call him.

1217
01:23:32,549 --> 01:23:35,052
He's on his way.
I don't know quite how...

1218
01:23:35,135 --> 01:23:38,263
Mr. Woburn, it isn't a matter
of days. It's a matter of minutes.

1219
01:23:38,347 --> 01:23:40,098
Now, you've got
to send some...

1220
01:23:40,182 --> 01:23:41,850
You've got to send
the police right away!

1221
01:23:41,934 --> 01:23:43,936
<i>Or do I have to go
to Albert Hall myself?</i>

1222
01:23:44,019 --> 01:23:45,479
That won't be necessary.

1223
01:23:45,562 --> 01:23:48,357
I'll have the chapel put
under immediate observation.

1224
01:23:48,440 --> 01:23:50,692
By the time you get back,
a police car should be there.

1225
01:23:50,776 --> 01:23:52,027
Please return
to your husband.

1226
01:23:52,110 --> 01:23:55,113
Tell him to come straight out of the
chapel and let the police take over.

1227
01:23:55,197 --> 01:23:56,740
Woburn, Special Branch.
Hold on.

1228
01:23:56,823 --> 01:23:58,367
I must ring off now,
Mrs. McKenna.

1229
01:23:58,450 --> 01:24:00,369
<i>Please believe me. I'll
have everything laid on.</i>

1230
01:24:32,484 --> 01:24:34,444
There's nobody there.

1231
01:24:34,528 --> 01:24:35,654
Are you Mrs. McKenna?

1232
01:24:35,737 --> 01:24:37,197
Yes, but there's
something wrong, Officer.

1233
01:24:37,281 --> 01:24:38,865
That place was full of
people just a few minutes ago,

1234
01:24:38,949 --> 01:24:39,950
and now there's nobody.

1235
01:24:40,033 --> 01:24:41,535
Our orders are to keep
it under observation

1236
01:24:41,618 --> 01:24:43,370
until the Scotland
Yard car arrives.

1237
01:24:43,453 --> 01:24:46,540
But my husband is in there.
There were 30 or 40 people...

1238
01:24:46,623 --> 01:24:47,958
When was this?

1239
01:24:48,041 --> 01:24:50,043
It was no more
than five minutes ago.

1240
01:24:50,127 --> 01:24:51,378
Let's take a look.

1241
01:24:51,461 --> 01:24:53,547
I've tried the door.
It's locked.

1242
01:24:53,630 --> 01:24:55,132
We'll have to
force it open.

1243
01:24:55,215 --> 01:24:57,467
I'm sorry, madam.
We can't break in.

1244
01:24:57,551 --> 01:25:00,012
Requires a search warrant.
It's the law, you see.

1245
01:25:00,095 --> 01:25:01,138
Well, can't we get one?

1246
01:25:01,221 --> 01:25:02,806
That all takes time.

1247
01:25:02,889 --> 01:25:04,850
We'll have a look
around, shall we?

1248
01:25:04,933 --> 01:25:06,018
Matthews,
take the other end.

1249
01:25:06,101 --> 01:25:07,519
All right.

1250
01:25:33,712 --> 01:25:34,755
There's no one there.

1251
01:25:34,838 --> 01:25:36,590
Are you quite certain this
place was full of people

1252
01:25:36,673 --> 01:25:37,924
only a few minutes ago?

1253
01:25:38,008 --> 01:25:41,470
Of course I'm certain. I was there
myself sitting next to my husband.

1254
01:25:41,553 --> 01:25:44,222
He sent me out to
call Scotland Yard.

1255
01:25:46,433 --> 01:25:49,519
Look, I'm afraid it's much
too complicated to explain why.

1256
01:25:49,603 --> 01:25:53,315
We'll just have to sit tight and wait
for the car to arrive from the Yard.

1257
01:25:59,905 --> 01:26:01,657
As far as we can make out,
there's no sign of life.

1258
01:26:01,740 --> 01:26:02,824
<i><i>Report back here.</i></i>

1259
01:26:02,908 --> 01:26:04,743
I see.
Very good, sir.

1260
01:26:04,826 --> 01:26:06,787
Walden, you stand by till
the car arrives from the Yard.

1261
01:26:06,870 --> 01:26:08,705
That's all, Matthews.
You're not leaving?

1262
01:26:08,789 --> 01:26:12,459
Orders, madam. Can we
give you a lift somewhere?

1263
01:26:12,542 --> 01:26:13,835
Yes, take me to
Albert Hall, please.

1264
01:26:13,919 --> 01:26:15,671
I'm afraid the Albert
Hall's a little bit off our beat.

1265
01:26:15,754 --> 01:26:17,381
Suppose we drop you
at the nearest taxi rank?

1266
01:26:17,422 --> 01:26:19,257
All right.

1267
01:27:37,711 --> 01:27:39,045
Wait here.

1268
01:27:45,844 --> 01:27:47,637
They're here.

1269
01:27:47,721 --> 01:27:49,347
Wait till I clear
the kitchen.

1270
01:27:59,775 --> 01:28:03,153
Everybody out! Come on. Into
the corridor. Five minutes only!

1271
01:28:03,236 --> 01:28:04,613
Come on!

1272
01:28:04,696 --> 01:28:08,158
Do as he tells you. Come
on. It'll only take a minute.

1273
01:28:08,241 --> 01:28:10,452
Come on. All of you out.

1274
01:28:10,535 --> 01:28:12,037
Why? Why?

1275
01:28:29,346 --> 01:28:31,223
All right. This way.

1276
01:28:34,392 --> 01:28:36,728
Always something funny
going on at this embassy.

1277
01:28:36,812 --> 01:28:38,730
Bringing people
in secret.

1278
01:28:38,814 --> 01:28:40,649
Give me the Swiss
embassy anytime.

1279
01:28:40,732 --> 01:28:42,818
There's neutrality
for you.

1280
01:30:04,232 --> 01:30:05,775
Please, may I
see the manager?

1281
01:30:05,859 --> 01:30:08,570
I'm sorry, madam. The
manager's on duty in the lobby.

1282
01:30:08,653 --> 01:30:09,696
So is his assistant.

1283
01:30:09,779 --> 01:30:10,780
I must speak
with one of them.

1284
01:30:10,864 --> 01:30:12,115
Which are they?

1285
01:30:12,198 --> 01:30:13,783
Over there somewhere.

1286
01:30:39,059 --> 01:30:41,394
You have a very nice
little boy, <i>madame.</i>

1287
01:30:42,020 --> 01:30:45,315
His safety will depend
upon you tonight.

1288
01:30:45,398 --> 01:30:48,485
Where is he?
Where is he?

1289
01:31:00,372 --> 01:31:01,831
Good evening.

1290
01:31:02,540 --> 01:31:03,708
Is that the
Prime Minister?

1291
01:31:03,792 --> 01:31:05,710
No, that's only
the Ambassador.

1292
01:31:05,794 --> 01:31:08,672
His Prime Minister's the
one with the bald head.

1293
01:31:34,239 --> 01:31:35,615
Your ticket, madam?

1294
01:31:35,699 --> 01:31:37,826
I'm sorry.
I'm looking for someone.

1295
01:41:30,626 --> 01:41:34,088
I saw the gun. He was
pointing it at the Prime Minister.

1296
01:41:34,171 --> 01:41:37,091
He was going to kill him, and
I realized that I had to scream.

1297
01:41:50,980 --> 01:41:52,023
Well, then he
didn't kill him?

1298
01:41:52,106 --> 01:41:55,151
Your wife saved him. It's
only a small flesh wound.

1299
01:41:56,902 --> 01:41:58,988
There they are.
Do please come over

1300
01:41:59,071 --> 01:42:00,865
and let the Prime Minister
thank you personally, would you?

1301
01:42:00,948 --> 01:42:03,367
I'm sure he'd like to.
It won't take very long.

1302
01:42:03,451 --> 01:42:06,579
Would you come along
with me? Don't be nervous.

1303
01:42:15,338 --> 01:42:17,465
Prime Minister,
this is the young lady.

1304
01:42:17,548 --> 01:42:19,800
Dear lady, I'm
forever in your debt.

1305
01:42:19,884 --> 01:42:21,927
This is her
husband.

1306
01:42:22,011 --> 01:42:24,930
I trust you'll permit me to
wait upon you tomorrow.

1307
01:42:25,014 --> 01:42:28,976
And to express to you
the depth of my gratitude.

1308
01:42:29,060 --> 01:42:30,811
It wasn't...

1309
01:42:30,895 --> 01:42:33,522
But it was, my
dear lady. It was.

1310
01:42:34,398 --> 01:42:36,108
Will you excuse us?

1311
01:42:37,652 --> 01:42:39,737
Excuse me,
but I have to go.

1312
01:42:47,995 --> 01:42:50,956
I think Mr. Buchanan
would like a word with you.

1313
01:42:56,921 --> 01:42:58,631
Where's our boy?
Where's Hank?

1314
01:42:58,714 --> 01:43:01,258
We can talk if
you'll come in here.

1315
01:43:04,929 --> 01:43:06,889
So you both knew the time
and the place all along.

1316
01:43:06,972 --> 01:43:08,182
Don't be a fool!

1317
01:43:08,265 --> 01:43:10,226
An odd coincidence,
both of you turning up here.

1318
01:43:10,309 --> 01:43:11,852
Yeah, it's a pity you didn't
contact your assistant.

1319
01:43:11,936 --> 01:43:13,521
He told us both
you were here.

1320
01:43:13,604 --> 01:43:14,689
I beg your pardon?

1321
01:43:14,772 --> 01:43:16,774
We need that help you
offered, Mr. Buchanan.

1322
01:43:19,694 --> 01:43:22,697
Sir, we've questioned the
woman. Said she bought a ticket

1323
01:43:22,780 --> 01:43:24,323
which happened to
place her in the same box

1324
01:43:24,407 --> 01:43:25,908
with the man who
did the shooting.

1325
01:43:25,991 --> 01:43:28,327
Didn't know anything. But
if she does, she isn't talking.

1326
01:43:28,411 --> 01:43:29,412
I'll see her later.

1327
01:43:29,495 --> 01:43:30,663
Very good, sir.

1328
01:43:30,746 --> 01:43:33,749
Please tell me everything
now. Everything.

1329
01:43:33,833 --> 01:43:37,169
There's still plenty of room
for hope, Mrs. McKenna.

1330
01:43:45,594 --> 01:43:47,304
His Excellency
will see you now.

1331
01:44:11,120 --> 01:44:12,913
And that's that,
Isuppose.

1332
01:44:12,997 --> 01:44:15,040
Yes. All right.

1333
01:44:19,211 --> 01:44:22,506
Excuse me, sir. I have
a lot to explain to you.

1334
01:44:23,507 --> 01:44:26,093
Something very
unusual has happened.

1335
01:44:27,720 --> 01:44:30,681
I also have to have the
money to pay the marksman.

1336
01:44:31,140 --> 01:44:35,895
Wouldn't that be superfluous,
considering that he's dead?

1337
01:44:43,027 --> 01:44:47,072
His aim wasn't quite as
good as you led me to expect.

1338
01:44:47,156 --> 01:44:50,743
The target merely received a
slight flesh wound in the arm.

1339
01:44:50,826 --> 01:44:52,703
Worse than useless.

1340
01:44:53,496 --> 01:44:57,625
Then your French friend
panicked, made a fatal crash,

1341
01:44:57,708 --> 01:45:00,044
landing on the floor
of the Albert Hall.

1342
01:45:04,465 --> 01:45:07,009
I don't see how you can
blame me for that, sir.

1343
01:45:07,092 --> 01:45:09,845
He was warmly recommended
by our people in Marrakech.

1344
01:45:09,929 --> 01:45:13,307
I'm glad that you are able
to treat the matter so lightly.

1345
01:45:13,390 --> 01:45:15,810
I'm holding a reception
here this evening.

1346
01:45:15,893 --> 01:45:17,645
In a few moments,
I have to welcome

1347
01:45:17,728 --> 01:45:19,814
our Prime Minister
as my guest of honor

1348
01:45:19,897 --> 01:45:24,193
when I hoped and expected that
he would be totally unable to attend.

1349
01:45:25,653 --> 01:45:28,489
That amuses you,
no doubt.

1350
01:45:28,572 --> 01:45:29,698
I don't know
what to say.

1351
01:45:29,782 --> 01:45:30,908
No.

1352
01:45:33,577 --> 01:45:35,454
But I do.

1353
01:45:35,538 --> 01:45:37,706
You have muddled
everything from the start.

1354
01:45:37,790 --> 01:45:40,209
Taking that child
with you from Marrakech.

1355
01:45:40,292 --> 01:45:43,879
Don't you realize that Americans
dislike having their children stolen?

1356
01:45:44,547 --> 01:45:47,299
How else could I make sure that
McKenna would keep his mouth shut?

1357
01:45:47,383 --> 01:45:50,219
Then to crown it all,
you get cold feet

1358
01:45:50,302 --> 01:45:52,388
and come running
along here to hide,

1359
01:45:52,471 --> 01:45:54,515
bringing the wretched
child with you.

1360
01:45:54,598 --> 01:45:58,018
Don't you see what you've done to
the diplomatic status of this embassy?

1361
01:45:58,102 --> 01:46:00,187
I didn't think.
I only thought we could...

1362
01:46:00,271 --> 01:46:03,065
How are you going to get
the child out of here?

1363
01:46:05,693 --> 01:46:08,320
No difficulty about that,
surely. The car...

1364
01:46:08,404 --> 01:46:12,867
With plainclothes detectives
planted right 'round this building?

1365
01:46:12,950 --> 01:46:15,786
You English intellectuals
will be the death of us all.

1366
01:46:15,870 --> 01:46:17,872
I'll think of something.
Only give me time.

1367
01:46:17,955 --> 01:46:19,623
Time.

1368
01:46:27,506 --> 01:46:32,303
I want the child removed from this
embassy and removed in such a way

1369
01:46:32,386 --> 01:46:37,725
that he won't be able to say
anymore where he has been tonight.

1370
01:46:37,808 --> 01:46:39,184
No!

1371
01:46:43,063 --> 01:46:44,899
I'll see to it.

1372
01:46:44,982 --> 01:46:49,445
Drayton! I trust that nothing
will go wrong this time.

1373
01:46:55,951 --> 01:46:58,203
It would be very
unfortunate for you if...

1374
01:47:00,873 --> 01:47:02,458
Yes, come in.

1375
01:47:04,335 --> 01:47:08,172
Your Excellency, the princess
should be arriving at any moment.

1376
01:47:21,018 --> 01:47:23,103
I recognized him.
He recognized me.

1377
01:47:23,187 --> 01:47:26,357
He tried to get away, made
a jump for it. That was all.

1378
01:47:26,440 --> 01:47:29,276
Trying to liquidate one
of their own big shots.

1379
01:47:29,360 --> 01:47:31,028
I wish they'd stick
to their usual custom

1380
01:47:31,111 --> 01:47:32,321
and do it in
their own country.

1381
01:47:35,115 --> 01:47:36,325
Yes?

1382
01:47:38,702 --> 01:47:40,412
Buchanan speaking.

1383
01:47:44,124 --> 01:47:45,668
Right. Thank you.

1384
01:47:47,169 --> 01:47:48,504
The Draytons are
at the embassy.

1385
01:47:48,587 --> 01:47:49,630
The what?

1386
01:47:49,713 --> 01:47:50,756
How do you know?

1387
01:47:50,839 --> 01:47:54,093
We have means of
finding out from the inside.

1388
01:47:54,176 --> 01:47:55,886
Well, look, if the Draytons
are at the embassy,

1389
01:47:55,970 --> 01:47:57,304
then our boy's
there too.

1390
01:47:57,388 --> 01:47:59,807
You're probably right,
but we can't do anything.

1391
01:47:59,890 --> 01:48:01,642
What do you mean,
you can't do anything?

1392
01:48:01,725 --> 01:48:04,603
Every embassy in a foreign
country has extraterritorial rights.

1393
01:48:04,687 --> 01:48:05,729
What's that?

1394
01:48:05,813 --> 01:48:08,023
As far as we're concerned, this
embassy stands on foreign soil.

1395
01:48:08,107 --> 01:48:11,694
So they can steal kids and
get away with it? What is this?

1396
01:48:11,777 --> 01:48:13,153
We could have
the Foreign Office

1397
01:48:13,237 --> 01:48:15,447
serve a writ on
the Ambassador.

1398
01:48:15,531 --> 01:48:19,034
You know, I'm not responsible for
the complications of international law.

1399
01:48:19,118 --> 01:48:23,747
If only we had some positive
proof that your boy really is in there.

1400
01:48:30,212 --> 01:48:33,215
Say, what's the phone
number of that embassy?

1401
01:48:33,298 --> 01:48:34,800
You got it?

1402
01:48:34,883 --> 01:48:35,926
What are you
thinking about?

1403
01:48:36,010 --> 01:48:37,594
Let me try something.

1404
01:48:37,678 --> 01:48:39,263
Grosvenor 0144.

1405
01:48:39,346 --> 01:48:41,515
Grosvenor 0144,
please.

1406
01:48:42,975 --> 01:48:45,644
That fellow that got shot's
a prime minister, isn't he?

1407
01:48:47,479 --> 01:48:51,608
Hello? Hello. I'd like to speak
to the Prime Minister, please.

1408
01:48:51,692 --> 01:48:53,235
Yeah, yeah. No, look.

1409
01:48:53,318 --> 01:48:56,196
Just tell him the lady that saved
his life would like to speak to him.

1410
01:48:56,280 --> 01:48:58,699
It's very important.
Yeah.

1411
01:48:58,782 --> 01:48:59,867
Ben, what do I say?

1412
01:48:59,950 --> 01:49:02,036
He wanted to visit with
us so he could thank you.

1413
01:49:02,119 --> 01:49:04,705
Tell him you want to come over
to the embassy right away, tonight,

1414
01:49:04,788 --> 01:49:07,541
'cause we're going to leave
London tomorrow. You see?

1415
01:49:07,624 --> 01:49:09,376
Hello? Here you are.

1416
01:49:10,002 --> 01:49:11,003
Hello?

1417
01:49:11,378 --> 01:49:14,631
My dear lady, this is
a charming surprise.

1418
01:49:19,470 --> 01:49:22,139
Delighted.
Delighted, delighted.

1419
01:49:22,222 --> 01:49:25,017
The Ambassador too
would be delighted.

1420
01:49:25,100 --> 01:49:27,644
Any friends of mine
are friends of his.

1421
01:49:31,482 --> 01:49:33,108
He said all right.

1422
01:49:33,859 --> 01:49:35,819
So if he asks you,
we're all set. You see?

1423
01:49:35,903 --> 01:49:36,904
But supposing
they don't?

1424
01:49:36,987 --> 01:49:39,740
Honey, have we ever been to a
party where they didn't ask you?

1425
01:49:39,823 --> 01:49:42,910
Now, your job is to
hold their attention, right?

1426
01:49:47,915 --> 01:49:50,250
Good evening.
It's Dr. and Mrs. McKenna.

1427
01:49:50,334 --> 01:49:52,878
How very nice
to see you.

1428
01:49:52,961 --> 01:49:54,588
The Prime Minister's
waiting for you.

1429
01:49:54,671 --> 01:49:57,091
Do come this way,
please.

1430
01:50:05,015 --> 01:50:06,433
<i>Madame.</i>

1431
01:50:07,184 --> 01:50:08,936
Good evening,
good evening.

1432
01:50:09,019 --> 01:50:10,771
Good evening.

1433
01:50:10,854 --> 01:50:14,691
This is the charming lady who
saved my life at the concert.

1434
01:50:14,775 --> 01:50:17,486
Madam, you saved
the life of the one man

1435
01:50:17,569 --> 01:50:20,322
who's irreplaceable
in our country.

1436
01:50:21,698 --> 01:50:24,618
I hear you are the famous
Jo Conway, <i>madame.</i>

1437
01:50:24,701 --> 01:50:26,411
Yes, I'm Jo Conway.

1438
01:50:26,495 --> 01:50:27,871
Perhaps we might...

1439
01:50:27,955 --> 01:50:30,791
I'm sure my wife would
be delighted to sing for you.

1440
01:50:30,874 --> 01:50:32,292
Wouldn't you, dear?

1441
01:50:32,376 --> 01:50:34,211
Well, it's been
quite some time.

1442
01:50:34,711 --> 01:50:37,381
I beg you, <i>madame.</i>
A tranquil coda

1443
01:50:37,464 --> 01:50:39,758
to conclude
a dramatic evening.

1444
01:50:39,842 --> 01:50:41,218
I'm very flattered.

1445
01:50:42,344 --> 01:50:46,974
Stanis? Would you put up
some chairs? And hurry up, please.

1446
01:50:47,057 --> 01:50:48,475
Ladies and gentlemen,

1447
01:50:48,559 --> 01:50:50,602
the famous Jo Conway
has gladly consented

1448
01:50:50,686 --> 01:50:52,855
to sing a few songs
for us tonight.

1449
